definitions: A combining form or prefix from Gr. poly`s, many; as, polygon, a figure of many angles; polyatomic, having many atoms; polychord, polyconic.

Neither very good nor very bad; middling; passable; tolerable; indifferent. In some Irish houses, where things are so-so, One gammon of bacon hangs up for a show. Goldsmith. He [Burns] certainly wrote some so-so verses to the Tree of Liberty. Prof. Wilson.
Combining forms signifying flat, level, plane; as planifolious, planimetry, plano-concave.
Arranged; plotted; -- in a bad sense; as, a put-up job. [Colloq.]

A prefix from the Latin ultra beyond (see Ulterior), having in composition the signification beyond, on the other side, chiefly when joined with words expressing relations of place; as, ultramarine, ultramontane, ultramundane, ultratropical, etc. In other relations it has the sense of excessively, exceedingly, beyond what is common, natural, right, or proper; as, ultraconservative; ultrademocratic, ultradespotic, ultraliberal, ultraradical, etc.
Past; gone by. "By-past perils." Shak.
A combining form, meaning somewhat resembling a cone; as, conico-cylindrical, resembling a cone and a cylinder; conico- hemispherical; conico-subulate.
Remote; as, the far-off distance. Cf. Far-off, under Far, adv.
Having only one slope or pitch; -- said of a roof.  -- n.

A shed or slight building placed against the wall of a larger structure and having a single-pitched roof; -- called also penthouse, and to-fall. The outer circuit was covered as a lean-to, all round this inner apartment. De Foe.
Red with heat; heated to redness; as, red-hot iron; red-hot balls. Hence, figuratively, excited; violent; as, a red-hot radical. Shak.
Transforming or converting a low-pressure current into one of high pressure; as, a step-up transformer.

A suffix denoting the agent (originally a woman), especially a person who does something with skill or as an occupation; as in spinster (originally, a woman who spins), songster, baxter (= bakester), youngster.
Consisting of two thicknesses, as cloth; double.
Woven double, as cloth or carpeting, by incorporating two sets of warp thread and two of weft.
Serving to connect at will one pipe or channel with either of two others; as, a two-way cock.
Designating a method of shaft excavation by drifting to a point below, and then raising instead of sinking.
Great as a man's arm. [Obs.] A wreath of gold, arm-gret. Chaucer.
See Brand-new.
Cast or laid aside; as, cast-off clothes.
Having eyes like a cat; hence, able to see in the dark.
United closely with another. [Obs.]
Deeply fetched or drawn. [Obs.] "Deep-fet groans." Shak.
Of or pertaining to the deeper parts of the sea; as, a deep-sea line (i. e., a line to take soundings at a great depth); deep-sea lead; deep-sea soundings, explorations, etc.
A prefix or combining form of Diamine.
Not having tears in the eyes.
Without wetting the feet.
Pertaining to the fibula.
Having toes connected by a membrane; palmiped; palmated; also, lobate.
Fresh from the forge; bright; quite new; brand-new. Charles reade. Your fire-new stamp of honor is scarce current. Shak.

Allowing passage in either of four directions; as, a four-way cock, or valve. Francis. Four-way cock, a cock connected with four pipes or ports, and having two or more passages in the plug, by which the adjacent pipes or ports may be made to communicate; formerly used as a valve in the steam engine, and now for various other purposes. In the illustration, a leads to the upper end of a steam engine cylinder, and b to the lower end; c is the steam pipe, and d the exhaust pipe.
Very fiery. Shak.
Pampered; fed luxuriously.
Of a strong red color.
Quite mad; -- raving crazy. Did I tell you about Mr. Garrick, that the town are horn-mad after Gray.
Badly educated or brought up; impolite; incivil; rude. See Note under Ill, adv.
Misapplied; treated badly.
Going; entering, as upon an office or a possession; as, an in- going tenant.
Cold as a metallic key; lifeless. [Formerly, a proverbial expression.] Shak. Milton.
Laid a side; cast-off.
Of or pertaining to, or suitable for, the commencement of the year; as, New-year gifts or odes.
Employing one hand; as, the one-hand alphabet. See Dactylology.
Taking place in the open air; outdoor; as, an open-air game or meeting.
Done (as bowling or pitching) with the arm raised above the shoulder. See Overhard. "An over-arm with a round-arm bowler." R. A. Proctor.
Having eyes like an owl's.
Having small, deep-set eyes.
Having the stigma visible at the throad of a gamopetalous corolla, while the stamens are concealed in the tube; -- said of dimorphous flowers. The opposite of Ant: thrum-eyed.
Having a firing pin to explode the cartridge; as, a pin-fire rifle.
Led by pixies; bewildered.
Made confident by drink. [Obs.]
Like a rat's tale in form; as, a rat-tail file, which is round, slender, and tapering. See Illust. of File.

Having hands red with blood; in the very act, as if with red or bloody hands; -- said of a person taken in the act of homicide; hence, fresh from the commission of crime; as, he was taken red-hand or red-handed.
Pertaining to, or characterized by, official formality. See Red tape, under Red, a.

Having the percussion fulminate in a rim surrounding the base, distinguished from center-fire; -- said of cartridges; also, using rim-fire cartridges; as, a rim-fire gun. Such cartridges are now little used.
Cut flat on the reverse, and with a convex face formed of triangular facets in rows; -- said of diamonds and other precious stones. See Rose diamond, under Rose. Cf. Brilliant, n.
Red as a rose; specifically (Zoöl.), of a pure purplish red color. Chaucer.
A Shakespearean word of uncertain meaning. Perhaps "fattened in the rump, pampered." "The rump-fed ronyon."

Lit., of or pert. to a lot or piece of sandy ground, -- hence, pert. to, or characteristic of, the policy or practices of the socialistic or communistic followers of the Irish agitator Denis Kearney, who delivered many of his speeches in the open sand lots about San Francisco; as, the sand-lot constitution of California, framed in 1879, under the influence of sand-lot agitation.
Born of the sea; produced by the sea. "Neptune and his sea-born niece." Waller.
Born at sea.
Secret. [Obs.] Marston.
Having the blue color of the sky; azure; as, a sky-blue stone. Wordsworth.
Quite new; brand-new; fire-new. "A span-new archbishop's chair." Fuller.
Upstart. [R.] Walpole.
Lofty and precipitous. [R.] Her stand she takes upon a steep-up hill. Shak.
Self-important and supercilious, [Colloq.] The airs of small, stuck-up, men. A. K. H. Boyd.
A combining form (also used adjectively), designating any one of a series of double derivatives of the azo and diazo compounds containing four atoms of nitrogen.
Measuring two feet; two feet long, thick, or wide; as, a two- foot rule.
Employing two hangs; as, the two-hand alphabet. See Dactylology.

Having or bearing two names; as, two-name paper, that is, negotiable paper on which at least two persons are severally liable as separate makers, or, usually, one as maker and one as indorser. [Colloq.]
Having two ports; specif.: Designating a type of two-cycle internal-combustion engine in which the admission of the mixture to the crank case is through a suction valve.
A combining form (also used adjectively) from uranium; -- used in naming certain complex compounds; as in uranoso-uranic oxide, uranoso-uranic sulphate.
Having the form of the letter U; specif. (Phys. Geog.),
of valleys, resembling a broad U in cross profile.
Capable of being washed off; not permanent or durable; -- said of colors not fixed by steaming or otherwise.
Skillful in finding the way; well acquainted with the way or route; wise from having traveled.
Having the toes united by a web for a considerable part of their length.
Properly or firmly set.
Well put together; having symmetry of parts.
Having the feet, or the shoes on the feet, wet.
Unsound; worthless; irresponsible; unsafe; -- said to have been originally applied to the notes of an insolvent bank in Michigan upon which there was the figure of a panther.
Running without control; running along the line without a train; as, a wild-cat locomotive.
Consumed, or rendered useless, by wearing; as, worn-out garments.
Having the sails set in the manner called wing-and-wing. [Sailors' slang]
Erected in the air; having no solid foundation; chimerical; as, an air-built castle.
Drawn in air; imaginary. This is the air-drawn dagger. Shak.
So tight as to be impermeable to air; as, an air-tight cylinder.
Quick-sighted; catching a glance as one goes.
Having blue eyes.
Quite new; bright as if fresh from the forge.
Having bad or speckled eyes. "A buck-eyed horse." James White.
Made of cast iron. Hence, Fig.: like cast iron; hardy; unyielding.
Former; previous; of times gone by; as, a cidevant governor.
See Clear-cut.
Having a sharp, distinct outline, like that of a cameo. She has . . . a cold and clear-cut face. Tennyson.
Concisely and distinctly expressed.
Closed while too cold to become thoroughly welded; -- said of a forging or casting.  -- n.
An imperfection caused by such insufficient welding.
Laid deeply; formed with cunning and sagacity; as, deep-laid plans.
Profoundly book-learned. "Great writers and deep-read men." L'Estrange.
Having the corners of the leaves turned down and soiled by careless or long-continued usage; -- said of a book. Statute books before unopened, not dog-eared. Ld. Mansfield.
Having a face resembling that of a dog. Dog-faced baboon (Zoöl.), any baboon of the genus Cynocephalus. See Drill.
Extremely weary. Shak.
Having eyes like a dove; meekeyed; as, dove-eyed Peace.
Having dry bones, or bones without flesh.
Constructed of uncemented stone. "Dry-stone walls." Sir W. Scott.
Having eyes wanting brightness, liveliness, or vivacity. Shak.
Having the ear perforated.
Possessed of the supposed evil eye; also, looking with envy, jealousy, or bad design; malicious. Shak.
Capable of being defended, or of making or affording defense. [Obs.] No fort so fencible, nor walls so strong. Spenser.
Fencible. [Obs.] Spenser.

Like the of a fish; acting, or producing something, like the tail of a fish. Fish-tail burner, a gas burner that gives a spreading flame shaped somewhat like the tail of a fish.  -- Fish-tail propeller (Steamship), a propeller with a single blade that oscillates like the tail of a fish when swimming.
Begotten by a fool. Shak.
Having sore or tender feet, as by reason of much walking; as, foot-sore cattle.
Done by the hand, without support, or the guidance of instruments; as, free-hand drawing. See under Drawing.
Pertaining to, or advocating, the non-extension of slavery; -- esp. applied to a party which was active during the period 1846-1856. [U.S.] -- Free"soil`er, n. [U.S.] -- Free"-soil`ism, n. [U.S.]
Unpracticed. [Obs.] Shak.
Spotted with whitish specks due to a disease, or produced artificially by spraying; -- said of tobacco used for cigar wrappers.
Having a gilt edge; as, gilt-edged paper.
Of the best quality; -- said of negotiable paper, etc. [Slang, U. S.]
Half-blooded. [Obs.]
Imperfectly acquainted with the rules of good-breeding; not well trained. Atterbury.
Informed by insufficient reading; superficial; shallow. Dryden.
Having, consisting of, or pertaining to, half tones; specif. (Photo-engraving),

pertaining to or designating plates, processes, or the pictures made by them, in which gradation of tone in the photograph is reproduced by a graduated system of dotted and checkered spots, usually nearly invisible to the unaided eye, produced by the interposition between the camera and the object of a screen. The name alludes to the fact that this process was the first that was practically successful in reproducing the half tones of the photograph.
Having a keen eye; sharpsighted; discerning.
Bred in high life; of pure blood. Byron.
Bred at home; domestic; not foreign. " Home-bred mischief." Milton. Benignity and home-bred sense. Wordsworth.
Not polished; rude; uncultivated. Only to me home-bred youths belong. Dryden.
Felt in one's own breast; inward; private. "Home-felt quiet. Pope.
More or less brittle when heated; as, hot-short iron.
Composed of ice.
Loaded with ice. "Ice-built mountains." Gray.
Leading a wicked life. [Obs.]
Done, attempted, or said, at an unsuitable or unpropitious time.
Applied to breeding from a male and female of the same parentage. See under Breeding.
Lying outside the visible spectrum at its red end; -- said of rays less refrangible than the extreme red rays.
Of a gray color, somewhat resembling that of iron freshly broken.  -- n.
An iron-gray color; also, a horse of this color.
Having the ironwork loose or corroded; -- said of a ship when her bolts and nails are so eaten with rust that she has become leaky.
Black as jet; deep black.
Rising to the knees; knee-high; as, water or snow knee-deep. Grass knee-deep within a month. Milton.
Sunk to the knees; as, men knee-deep in water. Where knee-deep the trees were standing. Longfellow.
Rising or reaching upward to the knees; as, the water is knee- high.
That knocks off; of or pertaining to knocking off.
That knocks out; characterized by knocking out; as, a knock-out blow; a knock-out key for knocking out a drill from a collet.
Pecuniarily embarrassed through owning much unprofitable land. [Colloq.]

Situated on the left; nearer the left hand than the right; as, the left-hand side; the left-hand road. Left-hand rope, rope laid up and twisted over from right to left, or against the sun; -- called also water-laid rope.
Letting alone. The let-alone principle, doctrine, or policy. (Polit. Econ.) See Laissez faire.
Of full size; of the natural size.
Languishing with love or amorous desire; as, a love-sick maid. To the dear mistress of my love-sick mind. Dryden.
Originating in, or expressive of, languishing love. Where nightingales their love-sick ditty sing. Dryden.
Characteristic of, or like, one bred in a low and vulgar condition of life; mean dishonorable; contemptible; as, low-lived dishonesty.
Having acute sight.
Extremely rash; foolhardy. See under March, the month. Sir W. Scott.
Having eyes like those of the mole; having imperfect sight.
Having eyes affected by the moon; moonblind; dim-eyed; purblind.
Shortsighted; purblind.
Applied to the Romance languages, as being mostly of Latin origin.
Same as Nott-headed. [Obs.] Shak.
Brown as a nut long kept and dried. "The spicy nutbrown ale." Milton.
Drawn by one horse; having but a single horse; as, a one-horse carriage.
Second-rate; inferior; small. [Slang, U.S.]
Having one side only, or one side prominent; hence, limited to one side; partial; unjust; unfair; as, a one-sided view or statement. "Unguarded and one-sided language." T. Arnold.
Growing on one side of a stem; as, one-sided flowers.  -- One`-sid"ed-ly, adv.  -- One`-sid"ed*ness, n.
With eyes widely open; watchful; vigilant. Shak.
Too busy; officious.
Having the upper jaw projecting beyond the lower, with the upper incisors in advance of the lower; -- said of dogs.
Having the pile worn off; threadbare.
Clad or crowned with pine trees; as, pine-clad hills.
Having small eyes. Holland.
Having a distorted foot, or a clubfoot or clubfeet. B. Jonson.
Having a face like a monkey or a pug; monkey-faced.
Hot-short; brittle when red-hot; -- said of certain kinds of iron.  -- Red"-short`ness, n.
Having a pink color like that of the rose, or like the pigment called rose pink. See Rose pink, under Rose.
Disposed to clothe everything with roseate hues; hence, sentimental. "Rose-pink piety." C. Kingsley.
Applied to the method delivering the ball in bowling, by swinging the arm horizontally. R. A. Proctor.
Free from payment of scot; untaxed; hence, unhurt; clear; safe. Do as much for this purpose, and thou shalt pass scot-free. Sir W. Scott. Then young Hay escaped scot-free to Holland. A. Lang.
Built at, in, or by the sea.
Of a beautiful bluish green color, like sea water on soundings.
Born or produced by one's self.
Made by one's self. Self-made man, a man who has risen from poverty or obscurity by means of his own talentss or energies.
One with itself; separate from others. [Obs.] Sylvester.
Cut sharply or definitely, or so as to make a clear, well- defined impression, as the lines of an engraved plate, and the like; clear-cut; hence, having great distinctness; well-defined; clear.
Eager in appetite or desire of gratification; affected by keen hunger; ravenous; as, an eagle or a lion sharp-set. The town is sharp-set on new plays. Pope.
Not to be injured by shot; shot-proof. [Obs.] Feltham.
Free from charge or expense; hence, unpunished; scot-free. [Obs.] Shak.
Sorrowful; mournful. [R.] "Sigh-born thoughts." De Quincey.
Not deeper than the skin; hence, superficial. Lowell.
An erroneous form of the Scotch word slughorne, or sloggorne, meaning slogan.
Quick; short; sharp; smart. Shak.
So named; called by such a name (but perhaps called thus with doubtful propriety).
Hung with spar, as a cave.
A combining form (also used adjectively) denoting relation to, or connection with, certain stannnous compounds.
Transforming or converting a current of high potential or pressure into one of low pressure; as, a step-down transformer.
Permitting one to stop over; as, a stop-over check or ticket. See To stop over, under Stop, v. i. [Railroad Cant, U.S.]
Dried by the heat of the sun. "Sun-dried brick." Sir T. Herbert.
Consisting of three distinct webs inwrought together in weaving, as cloth or carpeting; having three strands; threefold.
Connected with, or serving to connect, three channels or pipes; as, a three-way cock or valve.
Swung by the tide when at anchor; -- opposed to wind-rode.
Having the top or upper part too heavy for the lower part. Sir H. Wotton.
Proud to the highest degree. [R.] "This top-proud fellow." Shak.
Of inflexible honesty and fidelity; -- a term derived from the true, or Coventry, blue, formerly celebrated for its unchanging color. See True blue, under Blue.
Of genuine birth; having a right by birth to any title; as, a true-born Englishman.
Of a genuine or right breed; as, a true-bred beast. Shak.
Being of real breeding or education; as, a true-bred gentleman.
Having the circumference of a tun. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Giddy. [Obs.] Bacon.
Divided about half way from the border to the base into two segments; bifid.
Having two edges, or edges on both sides; as, a two-edged sword.
Same as Diphase, Diphaser.
Having two sides only; hence, double-faced; hypocritical.
Symmetrical.
Adapted for producing or for receiving either of two speeds; -- said of a power-transmitting device.
Capable of being thrown or cranked in two directions, usually opposite to one another; as, a two-throw crank; a two-throw switch.
Having two crank set near together and opposite to one another; as, a two-throw crank shaft.

Not having arrived at adult age, or at years of discretion; hence, raw; green; immature; boyish; childish. [Obs.] I myself have loved a lady, and pursued her with a great deal of under-age protestation. J. Webster.
Done (as bowling) with the arm not raised above the elbow, that is, not swung far out from the body; underhand. Cf. Over-arm and Round-Arm.
Not according to Moses; unlike Moses or his works. By this reckoning Moses should be most un Mosaic. Milton.
Covered with vines.
Having an eye of a very light gray or whitish color. Booth.
Worn by the waves. The shore that o'er his wave-worn basis bowed. Shak.

Going away; departing; of or pertaining to one who goes away. Way-going crop (Law of Leases), a crop of grain to which tenants for years are sometimes entitled by custom; grain sown in the fall to be reaped at the next harvest; a crop which will not ripen until after the termination of the lease. Burrill.
Born of a noble or respect able family; not of mean birth.
Having good breeding; refined in manners; polite; cultivated. I am as well-bred as the earl's granddaughter. Thackera
Of extensive reading; deeply versed; -- often followed by in.
Having seen much; hence, accomplished; experienced. [Obs.] Beau. & Fl. Well-seen in arms and proved in many a fight. Spenser.
Having good success.
White with heat; heated to whiteness, or incandescence.
Caused to ride or drive by the wind in opposition to the course of the tide; -- said of a vessel lying at anchor, with wind and tide opposed to each other. Totten.
Resembling that which is wise or sensible; judicious. The only wise-like thing I heard anybody say. Sir W. Scott.
Dyed before being made into cloth, in distinction from piece- dyed; ingrain.
Having two toes in front and two behind, as the trogons and woodpeckers.
See Alamort.
Extremely observant; watchful; sharp-sighted.
Sown during the last years of a tenancy, but not ripe until after its expiration; -- said of crops. Wharton.
Struck with awe. Milton.
Shaped like an awl.
Subulate. See Subulate. Gray.
Having a white face or a white mark on the face, as a stag.
Having sides inclining inwards, as a ship; -- opposed to wall- sided.
Shaped like a bat's wing; as, a bat's-wing burner.
Having the striking surface convex; -- said of hammers.
characterized by pomposity of manner. [Eng.]
Seen from above, as if by a flying bird; embraced at a glance; hence, generalas, a bird's-eye view.
Marked with spots resembling bird's eyes; as, bird's-eye diaper; bird's-eye maple.
Having black eyes. Dryden.
Having sore eyes; having the eyes dim with rheum; dim-sighted. The blear-eyed Crispin. Drant.
Lacking in perception or penetration; short-sighted; as, a blear- eyed bigot.
Habitually winking. Marlowe.
Somewhat impudent; lacking modesty; as, a bold-faced woman. I have seen enough to confute all the bold-faced atheists of this age. Bramhall.
Having a conspicuous or heavy face.
Having crooked legs, esp. with the knees bent outward. Johnson.
Eaten out by canker, or as by canker. [Obs.]
Weary; mournful.  Shak.
Rigged like a catboat.
Quite full; choke-full.
Full to the brim; quite full; chock-full.
Having a plump, short face.
As black as coal; jet black; very black. Dryden.
Brittle when cold; as, cold-short iron.
Having the ears cropped.
Affected with strabismus; squint-eyed; squinting.
Daggle-tailed; having the tail clogged with daglocks. "Dag- tailed sheep." Bp. Hall.
Greatly beloved. Shak.
Having a head shaped like that of a dog; -- said of certain baboons.
Noting a flight of stairs, consisting of two or more straight portions connected by a platform (landing) or platforms, and running in opposite directions without an intervening wellhole.
Doing nothing; inactive; idle; lazy; as, a do-nothing policy.
Niggardly.
Sharp-sighted as an eagle. "Inwardly eagle-eyed." Howell.

Thinking chiefly or most readily through, or in terms related to, the sense of hearing; specif., thinking words as spoken, as a result of familiarity with speech or of mental peculiarity; -- opposed to eye-minded.
Moving easily; hence, mild-tempered; ease-loving; inactive.
Resembling an egg in form; ovoid.
Having a neck like a ewe; -- said of horses in which the arch of the neck is deficent, being somewhat hollowed out. Youwatt.
Having one's mental imagery prevailingly of the visual type; having one's thoughts and memories mainly in the form of visual images. -- Eye"-mind`ed*ness, n.
Free from the power of love. "In maiden meditation, fancy- free." Shak.
Love-sick. Shak.
Having the nerves or veins arranged in a radiating manner; -- said of certain leaves, and of the winfs of some insects.
Having an expanded, or fan-shaped, tail; as, the fan-tailed pigeon.
Dull; stupid. Shak.
Sucked out of marches. "Fen-sucked fogs." Shak.
Having palmate feet.
Having lobate toes, as the coot and grebe.

Obtained directly from the first or original source; hence, without the intervention of an agent. One sphere there is . . . where the apprehension of him is first-hand and direct; and that is the sphere of our own mind. J. Martineau.

Of the highest excellence; preëminent in quality, size, or estimation. Our only first-rate body of contemporary poetry is the German. M. Arnold. Hermocrates . . . a man of first-rate ability. Jowett (Thucyd).
Having broad, loose, dependent ears. Shak.
Swift of foot. Shak.
Marked by, or as if by, the bite of flies. Shak.
Lucky, without judgment or contrivance. [Obs.] Spenser.
Foolishly hasty. [R.]
Foolishly liberal. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Fully expanded, as a blossom; as, a full-bloun rose. Denham.
Fully distended with wind, as a sail. Dryden.
Having reached the limits of growth; mature. "Full-grown wings." Lowell.
Having the orb or disk complete or fully illuminated; like the full moon.
Encompassed with gold.
Having green eyes.
Seeing everything through a medium which discolors or distorts. "Green-eyed jealousy." Shak.
Made sick by consciousness of guilt. "A guilt-sick conscience." Beau. c& El.
Ridden by a hag or witch; hence, afflicted with nightmare. Beattie. Cheyne.
Of a clear tint of brown, resembling brown human hair. It is composed of equal proportions of red and green.
Half-blooded.
Showing only part of the face; wretched looking; meager. Shak.
Imperfectly or partly heard to the end. And leave half-heard the melancholy tale. Pope.
As tight as can be made by the hand. Totten.
Unyielding; insensible to argument; uncompromising; strict. [Collog., U.S.]
Inflated, as with conceit.
Of lofty structure; tall. "High-built organs." Tennyson. The high-built elephant his castle rears. Creech.
Elevated; proud. "High-flown hopes." Denham.
Turgid; extravagant; bombastic; inflated; as, high-flown language. M. Arnold.
Highly rectified; very strongly alcoholic; as, high-proof spirits.
So as to stand any test. "We are high-proof melancholy." Shak.
High in tone or sound.
Elevated; high-principled; honorable. In whose high-toned impartial mind Degrees of mortal rank and state Seem objects of indifferent weight. Sir W. Scott.
Having a hip roof.
Kept at home.
Having a hooked or aquiline nose. Shak.
Fiery; violent; rash; hasty; impetuous; vehement. Macaulay.
Pinched or weakened by hunger. [Obs.] Milton.

Applied to those actions, or muscular movements, which are automatic expressions of dominant ideas, rather than the result of distinct volitional efforts, as the act of expressing the thoughts in speech, or in writing, while the mind is occupied in the composition of the sentence. Carpenter.
Idle-headed; stupid. [Obs.]
Boding evil; inauspicious; ill-omened. "Ill-boding stars." Shak.
Not well judged; unwise.
Ill-disposed. Byron.
Having unlucky omens; inauspicious. See Note under Ill, adv.
Pert. to the Indo-Aryans, or designating, or of, the Aryan languages of India.
Cased or covered with iron, as a vessel; ironclad.
Having iron sides, or very firm sides.
Dejected; chopfallen.

Created by judges or judicial decision; -- applied esp. to law applied or established by the judicial interpretation of statutes so as extend or restrict their scope, as to meet new cases, to provide new or better remedies, etc., and often used opprobriously of acts of judicial interpretation considered as doing this.
Having large, pendent ears. [Obs.] Bp. Hall.
Having a thin face.
slender or narrow; -- said of type the letters of which have thin lines, or are unusually narrow in proportion to their height. W. Savage.
Weary of living. Shak.
Having a light, springy step; nimble in running or dancing; active; as, light-foot Iris. Tennyson.
Having long arms; as, the long-armed ape or gibbon.
Extended to a great length. The cicadæ hushed their long-drawn, ear-splitting strains. G. W. Cable.
Having a long life; having constitutional peculiarities which make long life probable; lasting long; as, a long-lived tree; they are a longlived family; long-lived prejudices.
Not placing a high estimate on ecclesiastical organizations or forms; -- applied especially to Episcopalians, and opposed to high- church. See High Church, under High.
Pertaining to, or kept in, the lower case; -- used to denote the small letters, in distinction from capitals and small capitals. See the Note under 1st Case, n., 3.
Inclined in mind to low or unworthy things; showing a base mind. Low-minded and immoral. Macaulay. All old religious jealousies were condemned as low-minded infirmities. Bancroft.
Cut low in the neck; decollete; -- said of a woman's dress.
Having lungs that adhere to the pleura.
Wild; crack-brained.
Having many sides; -- said of figures. Hence, presenting many questions or subjects for consideration; as, a many-sided topic.
Interested in, and having an aptitude for, many unlike pursuits or objects of attention; versatile.  -- Ma"ny-sid`ed*ness, n.
Having a round, full face.
Overgrown with moss.
Spoken without sincerity; not heartfelt. "Mouth-made vows." Shak.
Silent and idle. [Colloq.] Boys can't sit mum-chance always. J. H. Ewing.
Having veins, or nerves, reticulated or netted; as, a net- veined wing or leaf.
Capable of seeing at night; sharp-eyed. "Your night-eyed Tiberius." B. Jonson.
Having feet adapted for swimming.
Looking on or forward.
Having a pearly speck in the eye; afflicted with the cataract.
Having a head like a pig; hence, figuratively: stupidity obstinate; perverse; stubborn. B. Jonson.  -- Pig"-head`ed*ness, n.
Having a tapered tail, with the middle feathers longest; -- said of birds.
Dark as a pitch; pitch-black.
Consisting of strands twisted together in the ordinary way; as, a plain-laid rope. See Illust. of Cordage.
Secure against harm by plots. Shak.
Worthy to be published. [R.]
So tight as to exclude rain as, a rain-tight roof.

In the United States navy, designating such a gun using fixed ammunition or metallic cartridge cases; -- distinguished from breech- loading (abbr. B. L.), applied to all guns loading with the charge in bags, and formerly from quick-fire. Rapid-fire guns in the navy also sometimes include automatic or semiautomatic rapid-fire guns; the former being automatic guns of not less than one inch caliber, firing a shell of not less than one pound weight, the explosion of each cartridge operating the mechanism for ejecting the empty shell, loading, and firing the next shot, the latter being guns that require one operation of the hand at each discharge, to load the gun. (2)

In the United States army, designating such a gun, whether using fixed or separate ammunition, designed chiefly for use in coast batteries against torpedo vessels and the lightly armored batteries or other war vessels and for the protection of defensive mine fields; -- not distinguished from quick-fire. (3)
In Great Britain and Europe used, rarely, as synonymous with quick-fire.

Having a long, tapering tail like that of a rat. Rat-tailed larva (Zoöl.), the larva of a fly of the genus Eristalis. See Eristalis.  -- Rat-tailed serpent (Zoöl.), the fer-de-lance.  -- Rat-tailed shrew (Zoöl.), the musk shrew.
Made already, or beforehand, in anticipation of need; not made to order; as, ready-made clothing; ready-made jokes.

Of or pertaining to a red letter; marked by red letters. Red- letter day, a day that is fortunate or auspicious; -- so called in allusion to the custom of marking holy days, or saints' days, in the old calendars with red letters.
Having a red tail. Red-tailed hawk (Zoöl.), a large North American hawk (Buteo borealis). When adult its tail is chestnut red. Called also hen hawck, and red-tailed buzzard.
Situated or being on the right; nearer the right hand than the left; as, the right-hand side, room, or road.

Chiefly relied on; almost indispensable. Mr. Alexander Truncheon, who is their right-hand man in the troop. Addison. Right-hand rope, a rope which is laid up and twisted with the sun, that is, in the same direction as plain-laid rope. See Illust. of Cordage.
Having the odor of rose water; hence, affectedly nice or delicate; sentimental. "Rose-water philantropy." Carlyle.
Wearing a coarse gown or shaggy garment made of rug. Beau. & Fl.
Having shaggy hair; shock-headed. [Obs.] Those rough rug-headed kerns. Shak.
Having a taste compounded of saltness and acidity; both salt and acid. [R.]
Sea-green in color. Shak.
Having defective sight; dim-sighted; purblind. Shak.
Of or pertaining to certain islands along the coast of South Carolina and Georgia; as, sea-island cotton, a superior cotton of long fiber produced on those islands.
Of a rich dark brown color, like the fur of the fur seal after it is dyed.
Surrounded, bounded, or protected by the sea, as if by a wall. Shak.
Moved by inherent power., without the aid of external impulse.
Of or pertaining to Semi-Arianism.
Half Saxon; -- specifically applied to the language intermediate between Saxon and English, belonging to the period 1150- 1250.
Shock-headed. Tennyson.
Impenetrable by shot.
Having a paddle wheel on each side; -- said of steam vessels; as, a side-wheel steamer.
Genuine; true; real; authentic; -- a term alluding to the comedy character Simon Pure, who is impersonated by another and is obliged to prove himself to be the "real Simon Pure."
Wanting skill. Shak.
Having flat sides; hence, tall, or long and lank. [Colloq. U. S.]
Of a dark gray, like slate.
Deep blue, like smalt.
Destitute of smell; having no odor. Daisies smell-less, yet most quaint. Beau & Fl.
Like or suiting a snail; as, snail-like progress.
Affected with blindness by the brilliancy of snow.  -- Snow"-blind`ness, n.
Enveloped in, or confined by, snow. Whittier.
White as snow; very white. "Snow-white and rose-red" Chaucer.
Having a short, flat nose, slightly turned up; as, the snub- nosed eel. Snub-nosed cachalot (Zoöl.), the pygmy sperm whale.

Having a soft or fragile shell. Soft-shell clam (Zoöl.), the long clam. See Mya.  -- Soft-shelled crab. (Zoöl.) See the Note under Crab, 1.  -- Soft-shelled turtle. (Zoöl.) Same as Soft tortoise, under Soft.
Calling himself; self-styled; pretended; would-be.
Having the eyes raised on a stalk, or peduncle; -- opposed to sessile-eyed. Said especially of podophthalmous crustaceans. Stalked- eyed crustaceans. (Zoöl.) See Podophthalmia.
Half blind.
Deep and precipitous, having steep descent. [R.] Wash me in steep-down gulfs of liquid fire. Shak.
Cold as a stone. Stone-cold without, within burnt with love's flame. Fairfax.
As dead as a stone.
As deaf as a stone; completely deaf.
Beaten, injured, or impaired by storms. Spenser.
Having a deep red color.
Overcome by, or affected with, sunstroke; as, sun-struck soldiers.

Having or consisting of three coats; -- applied to plastering which consists of pricking-up, floating, and a finishing coat; or, as called in the United States, a scratch coat, browning, and finishing coat.
Of or pertaining to three miles; as, the three-mile limit, or the limit of the marine belt (the three-mile belt or zone) of three miles included in territorial waters (which see) of a state.
Having three ports; specif.: Designating a type of two-cycle internal-combustion engine in which the mixture enters the crank case through a port uncovered by the piston near the end of its stroke.
Having the anthers raised above the stigma, and visible at the throat of the corolla, as in long-stamened primroses; -- the reverse of pin-eyed.
Having the shape of a top; (Bot.) cone-shaped, with the apex downward; turbinate.
Having the nostrils prolonged in the form of horny tubes along the sides of the beak; -- said of certain sea birds.
Belonging to the Tubinares.
Divided into two parts, somewhat after the manner of a fork; dichotomous.
Having two hands; -- often used as an epithet equivalent to large, stout, strong, or powerful. "Two-handed sway." Milton.
Used with both hands; as, a two-nanded sword. That two-handed engine [the sword]. Milton.
Using either hand equally well; ambidextrous.
Having two lips.
Divided in such a manner as to resemble the two lips when the mouth is more or less open; bilabiate.
Divided from the border to the base into two distinct parts; bipartite.
Divided from the border to the base into two distinct parts; bipartite.
Alternately disposed on exactly opposite sides of the stem so as to from two ranks; distichous.
Designating, or pert. to, a gear for reducing or increasing a velocity ratio two to one.
New; unprecedented; unparalleled. Swift.
Extending to the present time; having style, manners, knowledge, or other qualities that are abreast of the times. "A general up-to-date style of presentment."  Nature.
Having the shape of an urn; as, the urn-shaped capsules of some mosses.
Of or pertaining to a viceroy or viceroyalty. Macaulay.
Having sides nearly perpendicular; -- said of certain vessels to distinguish them from those having flaring sides, or sides tumbling home (see under Tumble, v. i.).
Warworn.
Having a left-hand twist; -- said of cordage; as, a water-laid, or left-hand, rope.
Having weak knees; hence, easily yielding; wanting resolution. H. James.
Having webbed feet; palmiped; as, a goose or a duck is a web- footed fowl.
Surrounded with happiness or prosperity. [Obs.] Fair and rich and young and wel-begone. Chaucer.
Fully known; generally known or acknowledged. A church well known with a well-known rite. M. Arnold.
Worn by the action of wheels; as, a wheel-worn road.
Having a pale or white face, as from fright. "Whey-faced cavaliers." Aytoun.

Having or covering an angle wider than the ordinary; -- applied to certain lenses of relatively short focus. Lenses for ordinary purposes have an angle of 50º or less. Wide-angle lenses may cover as much as 100º and are useful for photographing at short range, but the pictures appear distorted.
Fully awake; not Dickens.
Beset or overwhelmed with woe; immersed in grief or sorrow; woeful. Chaucer. So woe-begone was he with pains of love. Fairfax.
Incumbered with tall, woody hedgerows.
Extended throughout the world; as, world-wide fame. Tennyson.
Eaten, or eaten into, by a worm or by worms; as, worm-eaten timber. Concave as a covered goblet, or a worm-eaten nut. Shak.
Worn-out; old; worthless. [R.] Sir W. Raleigh.  -- Worm"-eat`en*ness, n. [R.] Dr. John Smith.
Having a sound, strong body; physically competent; robust. "Able-bodied vagrant." Froude.  -- A`ble-bod"ied*ness, n..
Having much intellectual power.  -- A`ble-mind"ed*ness, n.
Cited before, in the preceding part of a book or writing.
Slacked, or pulverized, by exposure to the air; as, air-slacked lime.
Of or pertaining to the Anglo-Saxons or their language.
Having a round, broad face, like an apple. "Apple-faced children." Dickens.
Of the color of ashes; a whitish gray or brownish gray.
An instrument blown with a reed, and resembling a clarinet, but of much greater compass, embracing nearly four octaves.
Having the shape of a widemouthed bell; campanulate.
Having a great belly; as, a big-bellied man or flagon; advanced in pregnancy.
Flighty; passing rapidly from one subject to another; not having the faculty of attention. Bacon.
Having a black, dark, or gloomy face or aspect.
Having blue veins or blue streaks.
Built with the stem nearly straight up and down.
See Cymbiform.
Deep as from the breast to the feet; as high as the breast. See him breast-deep in earth, and famish him. Shak.
High as the breast.
Having a short and thick neck like that of a bull. Sir W. Scott.
Built of, or in, the clouds; airy; unsubstantial; imaginary. Cowper. So vanished my cloud-built palace. Goldsmith.
Enlarged gradually at the end, as the antennæ of certain insects.
Boastful; defiant; exulting. Also used adverbially.
Affected with color blindness. See Color blindness, under Color, n.
Pectinate.
Having a temper not easily excited; free from passion.  -- Cool"-head`ed*ness, n.
White or pale, as the effect of fear, or as the natural complexion. Thou cream-faced loon. Shak.
As white as cream.
Having the tail cropped.
With arms crossed.
Having the lower ends of garments defiled by trailing in mire or filth; draggle-tailed.

Making a stroke without recoil; deadbeat. Dead-stroke hammer (Mach.), a power hammer having a spring interposed between the driving mechanism and the hammer head, or helve, to lessen the recoil of the hammer and reduce the shock upon the mechanism.
Bought at a high price; as, dear-bought experience.
Having dim sight; lacking perception.  -- Dim"-sight`ed*ness, n.
Inhuman; cruel. Shak.
Dyed twice; thoroughly or intensely colored; hence; firmly fixed in opinions or habits; as, a double-dyed villain.
Having a deceitful look. [R.] "Deceitful meanings is double- eyed." Spenser.
Having both sashes hung with weights and cords; -- said of a window.
Imperfectly baked; hence, not brought to perfection; unfinished; also, of weak or dull understanding. [Colloq.] Halliwell.
Easily molded; pliable.
Having a bill like that of a duck..
Having short legs, like a waddling duck; short-legged. Dryden.
Having the form of a duck's bill. Duck's-bill limpet (Zoöl.), a limpet of the genus Parmaphorus; -- so named from its shape.
Having a gloomy look.
Stupid.
Having evil dispositions or intentions; disposed to mischief or sin; malicious; malignant; wicked.  -- E"vil-mind`ed*ness, n.
Proceeding from office or authority.
Having fair or light-colored hair.
Unprejudiced; just; judicial; honest.  -- Fair"*mind`ed*ness, n.
Using fair speech, or uttered with fairness; bland; civil; courteous; plausible. "A marvelous fair-spoken man." Hooker.
Hypocritical. Shak.
False-hearted. Shak.
Close-handed; close-fisted; covetous; avaricious. [Obs.] Bacon.
Dull of apprehension.
Having a feat or trim body. [Obs.] Beau. & Fl.
Having a visible fiber embodied in the surface of; -- applied esp. to a kind of paper for checks, drafts, etc.
Injured as by fire; burned; -- said of manure which has lost its goodness and acquired an ashy hue in consequence of heat generated by decomposition.

Of the best class; of the highest rank; in the first division; of the best quality; first-rate; as, a first-class telescope. First- class car or First-class railway carriage, any passenger car of the highest regular class, and intended for passengers who pay the highest regular rate; -- distinguished from a second-class car.
Having five leaflets, as the Virginia creeper.
Having a flat foot, with little or no arch of the instep.
Firm-footed; determined. [Slang, U.S.]
Having a head with a flattened top; as, a flat-headed nail.
Bitten by a flea; as, a flea-bitten face.
White, flecked with minute dots of bay or sorrel; -- said of the color of a horse.

Having the outer tail feathers longer than the median ones; swallow-tailed; -- said of many birds. Fork-tailed flycatcher (Zoöl.), a tropical American flycatcher (Milvulus tyrannus).  -- Fork-tailed gull (Zoöl.), a gull of the genus Xema, of two species, esp. X. Sabinii of the Arctic Ocean.  -- Fork-tailed kite (Zoöl.), a graceful American kite (Elanoides forficatus); -- called also swallow-tailed kite.
Using profane, scurrilous, slanderous, or obscene language. Shak.
Pertaining to or engaged in the hunting of foxes; fond of hunting foxes.
Open-handed; liberal.
Not perplexed; having a mind free from care. Bacon.
Accustomed to speak without reserve. Bacon.  -- Free"-spo`ken-ness, n.
Of, pertaining to, or living in, water not salt; as, fresh-water geological deposits; a fresh-water fish; fresh-water mussels.
Accustomed to sail on fresh water only; unskilled as a seaman; as, a fresh-water sailor.
Unskilled; raw. [Colloq.] "Fresh-water soldiers." Knolles.
Full in form or shape; rounded out with flesh. The full-formed maids of Afric. Thomson.
Completely furnished wiith men, as a ship.
Having all its sails set,; hence, without restriction or reservation. Massinger.
Having large and strong or complete wings. Shak.
Beady for flight; eager. [Archaic] Beau. & Fl.
Having gagteeth. [Obs.]
Having interstices between the teeth. Dryden.
Goat-toothed; having a lickerish tooth; lustful; wanton. [Obs.]
Moving irregularly; flighty; fickle. [R.] Shak.
Mirror-faced; reflecting the sentiments of another. [R.] "The glass-faced flatterer." Shak.
Having a reverential and loving feeling towards God; religious. A brave good-fearing man. Tennyson.
Having prominent and distorted or rolling eyes. Ascham.
Gilded. [Obs.]
Mawkishly or weakly good; exhibiting goodness with silliness. [Colloq.]
Bog-bellied. [Obs.]
Of or pertaining to a grand duke. H. James.
Green with grass.
Of the color of grass; clear and vivid green.
Overgrown with grass; as, a grass-grown road.
Having characteristics that are partly Greek and partly Roman; as, Greco-Roman architecture.
Partially decked. The half-decked craft . . . used by the latter Vikings. Elton.
Done or happening at intervals of half an hour.
Of half the whole or ordinary length, as a picture.
Weak in intellect; silly.
Two in a year; semiannual.  -- adv. Twice in a year; semiannually.
Without a visible hammer; -- said of a gun having a cock or striker concealed from sight, and out of the way of an accidental touch.
Having wings that are like hands in the structure and arrangement of their bones; -- said of bats. See Cheiroptera.
Having hard or strong hands; as, a hard-fisted laborer.
Close-fisted; covetous; niggardly. Bp. Hall.
contested; as, a hard-fought battle.
Having hard hands, as a manual laborer. Hard-handed men that work in Athens here. Shak.
Having sound judgment; sagacious; shrewd.  -- Hard"-head`ed*ness, n.
Made in the manner of a hawser. Cf. Cable-laid, and see Illust. of Cordage.
Lugged or dragged by the head. [R.] "The head-lugged bear." Shak.
Having the heart or affections free; not in love. Shak.
With unbroken courage; undismayed.
Of a single and sincere heart. If he keeps heart-whole towards his Master. Bunyan.
Wearing heavy or complete armor; carrying heavy arms.
Clumsy; awkward.
Cowardly; timid; chicken-hearted. Udall.
Of or pertaining to, or favoring, the party called the High Church, or their doctrines or policy. See High Church, under High, a.
Overbearing; oppressive; arbitrary; violent; as, a high-handed act.
Proud; arrogant. [Obs.] Be not high-minded, but fear. Rom. xi. 20.
Having, or characterized by, honorable pride; of or pertaining to elevated principles and feelings; magnanimous; -- opposed to mean. High-minded, manly recognition of those truths. A. Norton.
Having high antlers; bearing full-grown antlers aloft.
Elevated; raised aloft; upreared.
Elated with great ideas or hopes. Milton.
Having a high or noble spirit; honorable. E. Everett.
Strung to a high pitch; spirited; sensitive; as, a high-strung horse.

Thoughtless; giddy; flighty; also, haughty; patronizing; as, to be in hoity-toity spirits, or to assume hoity-toity airs; used also as an exclamation, denoting surprise or disapprobation, with some degree of contempt. Hoity-toity! What have I to do with dreams Congreve.
Driven to the end, as a nail; driven close.
Sweet as honey. Chaucer.
Having a strongly curved bill.
Having hot blood; excitable; high-spirited; irritable; ardent; passionate.
Ardent in temper; violent; rash; impetuous; as, hot-brained youth. Dryden.
Of an excitable or irritable temperament; irascible. Milton.
Headstrong. That hot-mouthed beast that bears against the curb. Dryden.
Spangled with ice. Mounting up in icy-pearled car. Milton.
Foolish; stupid. [Obs.] "The superstitious idle-headed eld." Shak.
Delirious; infatuated. [Obs.] L'Estrange.
Wanting beauty or attractiveness; deformed; ugly; ill-looking. Ill-favored and lean-fleshed. Gen. xli. 3. -- Ill`-fa"vored*ly, adv.  -- Ill`-fa"vored*ness, n.
Having a bad look; threatening; ugly. See Note under Ill, adv.
Of habitual bad temper; peevish; fractious; cross; crabbed; surly; as, an ill-natured person.
Dictated by, or indicating, ill nature; spiteful. "The ill-natured task refuse." Addison.
Intractable; not yielding to culture. [R.] "Ill-natured land." J. Philips.  -- Ill`-na"tured*ly, adv.  -- Ill`-na"tured*ness, n.
Fated to be unfortunate; unlucky; as, an ill-starred man or day.
Closefisted; stingy; mean.
Covered with ivy.
Double-faced; deceitful. Janus-faced lock, one having duplicate faces so as to go upon a right or a left hand door, the key entering on either side indifferently. Knight.
Built hastily and of bad materials; as, jerry-built houses. [Colloq. Eng.]
Rigged for temporary service. See Jury, a.
Having the form or shape of a kidney; reniform; as, a kidney- shaped leaf. Gray.
See Knock-kneed.
Having the legs bent inward so that the knees touch in walking. [Written also knack-kneed.]
Having thin, transparent, reticulated wings; as, the lace- winged flies.
Having a lap joint, or lap joints, as many kinds of woodwork and metal work.
Possessing much land.
Having a slender elongated form, like a lath; -- said of the feldspar of certain igneous rocks, as diabase, as seen in microscopic sections.
Abiding the law; waiting for the operation of law for the enforcement of rights; also, abiding by the law; obedient to the law; as, law-abiding people.
Having leaflike expansions on the legs; -- said of certain insects; as, the leaf-footed bug (Leptoglossus phyllopus).
Having but little sense or shrewdness.
Having the left hand or arm stronger and more dexterous than the right; using the left hand and arm with more dexterity than the right.
Clumsy; awkward; unlucky; insincere; sinister; malicious; as, a left-handed compliment. The commendations of this people are not always left-handed and detractive. Landor.

Having a direction contrary to that of the hands of a watch when seen in front; -- said of a twist, a rotary motion, etc., looked at from a given direction. Left-handed marriage, a morganatic marriage. See Morganatic.  -- Left-handed screw, a screw constructed to advance away from the observer, when turned, as in a nut, with a left-handed rotation. An ordinary wood screw is right-handed.
Giving life or spirit; having power to give life; inspiriting; invigorating.
That saves life, or is suited to save life, esp. from drowning; as, the life-saving service; a life-saving station.
Armed with light weapons or accouterments.
Having a like disposition or purpose; of the same mind. Tillotson.
Having white, delicate hands.
Having an enlarged liver. Dunglison.
Lobiped.
Having a long horn or horns; as, a long-horned goat, or cow; having long antennæ, as certain beetles (Longicornia).
Long-breathed; hence, tediously long in speaking; consuming much time; as, a long-winded talker.  -- Long"-wind"ed*ness, n. A tedious, long-winded harangue. South.
Having a loud voice; noisy; clamorous. Byron.
Furnished or built with short studs; as, a low-studded house or room.
Having a curved spine.
Having many faculties; versatile; many-sided.
Being about the middle of the ordinary age of man; between 30 and 50 years old.

Having a head like that of a nail; formed so as to resemble the head of a nail. Nail-headed characters, arrowheaded or cuneiform characters. See under Arrowheaded.  -- Nail-headed molding (Arch.), an ornament consisting of a series of low four-sided pyramids resembling the heads of large nails; -- called also nail-head molding, or nail-head. It is the same as the simplest form of dogtooth. See Dogtooth.
Affectedly pretty; weakly sentimental; finical; insipid. Thackeray. Namby-pamby madrigals of love. W. Gifford.
Having the feet so near together that they interfere in traveling. Shak.
Of, pert. to, or designating, modern Hebrew, or Hebrew of later date than the Biblical.
Of or pertaining to Neo-Kantianism.
Having the hair cut close. [Obs.] Chapman.
Like an old maid; prim; precise; particular.
Generous; liberal; munificent.  -- O"pen-hand`ed*ness, n. J. S. Mill.
Bareheaded. [Obs.]
Being out of the house; being, or done, in the open air; outdoor; as, out-of-door exercise. See Out of door, under Out, adv. Amongst out-of-door delights. G. Eliot.
Of the form of a pear.
Black as pitch or tar.
Having the arris defined by a line beyond which the rock is cut away, so as to give nearly true edges; -- said of squared stones that are otherwise quarry-faced.
Proud of rank or office. Beau. & Fl.
Broken out, or marked, with smallpox; pock-fretten.
Pockmarked; pitted.
Directed in a line toward the object aimed at; aimed directly toward the mark.

Hence, direct; plain; unqualified; -- said of language; as, a point-blank assertion. Point-blank range, the extent of the apparent right line of a ball discharged.  -- Point-blank shot, the shot of a gun pointed directly toward the object to be hit.
After death; as, post-mortem rigidity. Post-mortem examination (Med.), an examination of the body made after the death of the patient; an autopsy.
Having a protuberant belly, like the bottom of a pot.
Having the courage given by drink. Smollett.
Having erect, pointed ears; -- said of certain dogs. Thou prick-eared cur of Iceland. Shak.
Proof against proofs; obstinate in the wrong. "That might have shown to any one who was not proof-proof." Whateley.
Pertaining to, or designating, architecture, in which the beginnings of the Doric style are supposed to be found.
Having a conspicuous tuft of feathers on the legs.
Affected with purse pride; puffed up with the possession of riches.
White-faced; -- used contemptuously. Clarke.
Creating anew; as, re-creative power.
Formed by right lines; rectilineal; as, a right-lined angle.

Having a well defined ring of color around the neck. Ring- necked duck (Zool.), an American scaup duck (Aythya collaris). The head, neck, and breast of the adult male are black, and a narrow, but conspicuous, red ring encircles the neck. This ring is absent in the female. Called also ring-neck, ring-necked blackhead, ringbill, tufted duck, and black jack.
Having the tail crossed by conspicuous bands of color. Ring- tailed cat (Zoöl.), the cacomixle.  -- Ring-tailed eagle (Zoöl.), a young golden eagle.
Having the tail, or lower part of the body, bright red.
Having a peculiar pouch developed near the front edge of the wing; -- said of certain bats of the genus Saccopteryx.
Having a tooth or teeth like those of a saw; serrate.
Of the second size, rank, quality, or value; as, a second-rate ship; second-rate cloth; a second-rate champion. Dryden.
Humbled by consciousness of inferiority, unworthiness, guilt, or shame.

Acting of or by one's self or by itself; -- said especially of a machine or mechanism which is made to perform of or for itself what is usually done by human agency; automatic; as, a self-acting feed apparatus; a self-acting mule; a self-acting press.
Acting of one's self or of itself; acting without depending on other agents.
Moving by inherent power, without the aid of external impulse.
Suicide.
Taught by one's own efforts.
Governed by one's own will; not yielding to the wishes of others; obstinate.

Designating an internal-combustion engine of a type resembling the Diesel engine in using as fuel heavy oil which is injected in a spray just before the end of the compression stroke and is fired without electrical ignition. The fuel is sprayed into an iron box (called a hot bulb or hot pot) opening into the combustion chamber, and heated for ignition by a blast-lamp until the engine is running, when it is, ordinarily, kept red hot by the heat of combustion.
Having a mixture of seriousness and sport; serious and comical.
Having shaggy hair. Shak.
Borne on shards or scaly wing cases. "The shard-borne beetle." Shak.
Over-bashful; sheepish.
Rigged like a ship, that is, having three masts, each with square sails.
Having little time to run from the date. "Thy short-dated life." Sandys.
Not living or lasting long; being of short continuance; as, a short-lived race of beings; short-lived pleasure; short-lived passion.
Having little wit; not wise; having scanty intellect or judgment.
Composed of four strands, and laid right-handed with a heart, or center; -- said of rope. See Illust. under Cordage.
Having a gray color with a silvery luster; as, silver-gray hair.
Dull of apprehension; not possessing quick intelligence.
Having a feminine countenance or complexion; smooth-faced; girlish. Fenton.
Slow-moving, like a snail. Bid the snail-paced Ajax arm for shame. Shak.

God's nails, or His nails, that is, the nails with which the Savior was fastened to the cross; -- an ancient form of oath, corresponding to 'Od's bodikins (dim. of body, i.e., God's dear body). Beau & Fl.
Having the top capped or covered with snow; as, snow-capped mountains.
Having the fin rays cartilaginous or flexible; without spines; -- said of certain fishes.
Weak in intellect.
Speaking softly; having a mild or gentle voice; hence, mild; affable.

Drawn out from a heated solid bar, as by a process of spiral rolling which first hollows the bar and then expands the cavity by forcing the bar over a pointed mandrel fixed in front of the rolls; - - said of a weldless tube.

Having one or more spurs on the bend of the wings. Spur-winged goose (Zoöl.), any one of several species of long-legged African geese of the genus Plectropterus and allied genera, having a strong spur on the bend of the wing, as the Gambo goose (P. Gambensis) and the Egyptian, or Nile, goose (Alopochen Ægyptiaca).  -- Spur-winged plover (Zoöl.), an Old World plover (Hoplopterus spinosus) having a sharp spur on the bend of the wing. It inhabits Northern Africa and the adjacent parts of Asia and Europe.
Having eyes that quint; having eyes with axes not coincident; cross-eyed.
Looking obliquely, or asquint; malignant; as, squint-eyed praise; squint-eyed jealousy.
Having the mandibles large and palmate, or branched somewhat like the antlers of a stag; -- said of certain beetles.
Having a paddle wheel at the stern; as, a stern-wheel steamer.
Blind as a stock; wholly blind.
Still as a stock, or fixed post; perfectly still. His whole work stands stock-still. Sterne.
As blind as a stone; completely blind.
As still as a stone. Shak.
Not liable to stumble or fall; as, a sure-footed horse.
Having the back hollow or sagged, whether naturally or as the result of injury or weakness; -- said of horses and other animals.
Squint-eyed. [Prov. Eng.]
Made by a tailor or according to a tailor's fashion; -- said specif. of women's garments made with certain closeness of fit, simplicity of ornament, etc.
Private; confidential; familiar. She avoided tête-à-tête walks with him. C. Kingsley.
Having no thralls.
Not enslaved; not subject to bonds.
Resembling a thrall, or his condition, feelings, or the like; slavish. Servile and thrall-like fear. Milton.
Designating, or pert. to, a photomechanical process employing printings in three colors, as red, yellow, and blue.
Having three lobes. Three-lobed leaf (Bot.), a leaf divided into three parts, the sinuses extending not more than half way to the middle, and either the parts of the sinuses being rounded.
Having the quality of three-pile; best; most costly. [R.] Thou art good velvet; thou 'rt three-piled piece. Shak.
Fig.: Extravagant; exaggerated; high-flown. "Three-piled hyperboles." Shak.
Accustomed to wearing three-pile; hence, of high rank, or wealth. [Obs.] "Three-piled people." Beau. & Fl.
Thrice twenty; sixty.
Having three sides, especially three plane sides; as, a three- sided stem, leaf, petiole, peduncle, scape, or pericarp.
Destitute of the power of distinct articulation; having an impediment in the speech, esp. when caused by a short frænum.
Unable to speak freely, from whatever cause. Love, therefore, and tongue-tied simplicity. Shak.

Of or pertaining to tragi-comedy; partaking of grave and comic scenes.  -- Trag`-com"ic*al*ly, adv. Julian felt toward him that tragi-comic sensation which makes us pity the object which excites it not the less that we are somewhat inclined to laugh amid our sympathy. Sir W. Scott.
Having erect, pointed ears; prick-eared; -- said of certain dogs.
Ready to fall; dilapidated; ruinous; as, a tumble-down house. [Colloq.]
Having a large, protuberant belly, or one shaped like a tun; pot-bellied.
Having a projecting under jaw; prognathous. [Obs.] Holland.
Double-tongued; deceitful. Sandys.
Unhoped; unexpected.
Of or pertaining to the Urals and the Altai; as the Ural- Altaic, or Turanian, languages.
Formed like a vase, or like a common flowerpot.
Prevented by a flood from proceeding.
So tight as to retain, or not to admit, water; not leaky.
Having a weak mind, either naturally or by reason of disease; feebleminded; foolish; idiotic.  -- Weak"-mind`ed*ness, n.
Being in good condition. [Obs. or Archaic] They also shall bring forth more fruit in their age, and shall be fat and well-liking. Bk. of Com. Prayer (Ps. xcii.).
Speaking well; speaking with fitness or grace; speaking kindly. "A knight well-spoken." Shak.
Spoken with propriety; as, well-spoken words.
Shaped like the lash of a whip; long, slender, round, and tapering; as, a whip-shaped root or stem.
Whitewashed or plastered with lime. "White-limed walls." Shak.
Of a color between white and brown. Pegge.

Having the power of breathing impaired by the rupture, dilatation, or running together of air cells of the lungs, so that while the inspiration is by one effort, the expiration is by two; affected with pulmonary emphysema or with heaves; -- said of a horse. Youatt.
Shaken by the wind; specif. (Forestry),
affected by wind shake, or anemosis (which see, above).
Having wings attached to the feet; as, wing-footed Mercury; hence, swift; moving with rapidity; fleet. Drayton.
Having part or all of the feet adapted for flying.
Having the anterior lobes of the foot so modified as to form a pair of winglike swimming organs; -- said of the pteropod mollusks.
Having the anterior limbs or hands adapted for flight, as the bats and pterodactyls.
Having pinnate or pinnately divided leaves.
Having some or all of the tail quills terminated in a long, slender, pointed shaft, without a web or barbules.
Thin and pale; weak; without strength or substance; -- originally said of liquids. Fig., weak-minded; spiritless. A weak wishy-washy man who had hardly any mind of his own. A. Trollope.
Barren of wit; destitute of genius. Examiner.
Having a shriveled, thin, withered face.
Pertaining to, or characteristic of, working days, or workdays; everyday; hence, plodding; hard-working. O, how full of briers in this working-day world. Shak.
Shaped like a worm; as, a worm-shaped root.
Done at an improper time; ill-timed.
Having two masts with fore-and-aft sails, but differing from a schooner in that the after mast is very small, and stepped as far aft as possible. See Illustration in Appendix.
Having yellow eyes. Yellow-eyed grass (Bot.), any plant of the genus Xyris.
Electrically polarized like the surface of the zinc presented to the acid in a battery, which has zincous affinity. [Obs.]
Having acute angles; as, an acute-angled triangle, a triangle with every one of its angles less than a right angle.
Characterized by afterwit; slow-witted. Tyndale.
Like-minded. [Obs.]
Covered with defensive plates of metal, as a ship of war; steel-clad. This day will be launched . . . the first armor-plated steam frigate in the possession of Great Britain. Times (Dec. 29, 1860).
Awe-struck.
Having legs that bend inward at the knees.
Having crooked legs.
Having the nerves radiating from the base; -- said of leaves.
Expanding at the mouth; as, a bell-mouthed gun. Byron.
Having black eyebrows. Hence: Gloomy; dismal; threatening; forbidding. Shak. Dryden.
Written or printed in black letter; as, a black-letter manuscript or book.
Given to the study of books in black letter; that is, of old books; out of date. Kemble, a black-letter man! J. Boaden.
Of or pertaining to the days in the calendar not marked with red letters as saints' days. Hence: Unlucky; inauspicious.
Built with the stem nearly straight up and down.
Versed in books; having knowledge derived from books. [Often in a disparaging sense.] Whate'er these book-learned blockheads say, Solon's the veriest fool in all the play. Dryden.
Having the nose bottleshaped, or large at the end. Dickens.
Of or pertaining to the Brahmans or to their doctrines and worship.
Having horns spreading widely.
Having broad, or relatively broad, leaves. Keats.
Capable of resisting the force of a bullet. Bullet tree. See Bully tree.  -- Bullet wood, the wood of the bullet tree.
Having a bunch on the back; crooked. "Bunch-backed toad." Shak.
Stupid. [Obs.] Shak.
With well-proportioned, unblemished limbs; as, a clean-limbed young fellow. Dickens.
Having a clear understanding; quick of perception; intelligent. "He was laborious and clear-headed." Macaulay.  -- Clear"-head`ed*ness, n.
Having a clear physical or mental vision; having a clear understanding.
Having a cloven foot.
Closely united.
Firmly barred or closed.
Fitting the body exactly; setting close, as a garment. Ayliffe.
Having clouds resting on the top or head; reaching to the clouds; as, cloud-capped mountains.
Giddy; rash. Milton.
Having cold blood; -- said of fish or animals whose blood is but little warmer than the water or air about them.
Deficient in sensibility or feeling; hard-hearted.
Not thoroughbred; -- said of animals, as horses, which are derived from the common stock of a country.
Wanting passion or feeling; indifferent.  -- Cold"-heart`ed*ness, n.
Consisting of a series of parallel cones, each made up of many concentric cones closely packed together; -- said of a kind of structure sometimes observed in sedimentary rocks.
Faced or covered with copper; as, copper-faced type.

Paly, and then divided fesswise, so that each vertical piece is cut into two, having the colors used alternately or counterchanged. Thus the escutcheon in the illustration may also be blazoned paly of six per fess counterchanged argent and azure.
A term used when a narrow ribbon of veneer is inserted into the surfase of any piece of furniture, wainscoting, etc., so that the grain of it is contrary to the general surface.
Marked with crow's-feet, or wrinkles, about the eyes. [Poetic] Do I look as if I were crow-trodden Beau. & FL.
Having a deckle edge; as, deckle-edged paper; a deckle-edged book.
Having a loud and sonorous voice. "Deep-mouthed dogs." Dryden.
Having a deep waist, as when, in a ship, the poop and forecastle are much elevated above the deck.
Having two faces designed for use; as, a double-faced hammer.
Deceitful; hypocritical; treacherous. Milton.
Of, or performed in, the fastest time or step in marching, next to the run; as, a double-quick step or march.
Armed with dreaded bolts. "Dread-bolted thunder." [Poetic] Shak.
Stupid; doltish. Shak.
Having poor eyesight.
Having the wings of an eagle; swift, or soaring high, like an eagle. Shak.
Relating to the Eastern Islands; East Indian. [R.] Ogilvie.
Gilded by means of voltaic electricity.
Sized by a machine, and not while in the pulp; -- said of paper. Knight.
Designating, made of, or relating to, flour including a considerable part of the bran.
Having a bad countenance or appearance; ill-favored; blemished; deformed. Bacon. -- E"vil-fa`vored*ness, n. Deut. xvi. 1.
Excitomotory; as, excito-motor power or causes.
Inserted exterior to the eyes; -- said of the antennæ of certain insects.
Well-disposed. "A fair-natured prince." Ford.
Made or done in pleasant weather, or in circumstances involving but little exposure or sacrifice; as, a fair-weather voyage. Pope.
Appearing only when times or circumstances are prosperous; as, a fair-weather friend. Fair-weather sailor, a make-believe or inexperienced sailor; -- the nautical equivalent of carpet knight.
Gross; lubberly. Peace, ye fat-kidneyed rascal ! Shak.
Of the color of a fawn; light yellowish brown.
Bellying or swelling out on the under side; as, a fish-bellied rail. Knight.
Having broad, hangling lips. [R.] Shak.
Having the habit of catching insects on the wing.
Using language scurrilous, opprobrious, obscene, or profane; abusive. So foul-mouthed a witness never appeared in any cause. Addison.
Consisting of four horses controlled by one person; as, a four- in-hand team; drawn by four horses driven by one person; as, a four- in-hand coach.  -- n.
A team of four horses driven by one person; also, a vehicle drawn by such a team. As quaint a four-in-hand As you shall see. Tennyson.
Having four wheels.
Open; frank; unreserved; liberal; generous; as, free-hearted mirth.  -- Free"-heart`ed*ly, adv.  -- Free"-heart`ed*ness, n.
Yielding free gold or silver; -- said of certain ores which can be reduced by crushing and amalgamation, without roasting or other chemical treatment. Raymond.
Speaking without reserve. Bp. Hall.
Having a full supply of blood.
Of pure blood; thoroughbred; as, a full-blooded horse.
Like a perfect blossom. "Full-bloomed lips." Crashaw.
Full of courage or confidence. Shak.
Thoughtless; unsteady.
Given to viewing one's self in a glass or mirror; finical. [Poetic] Shak.
Shaped like a globe.
Having a cheerful spirit and demeanor; good-tempered. See Good- natured.
Handsome.

synonyms: good-natured, good-tempered, good-humored. good-natured denotes a disposition to please and be pleased. good-tempered denotes a habit of mind which is not easily ruffied by provocations or other disturbing influences. good-humored is applied to a spirit full of ease and cheerfulness, as displayed in one's outward deportment and in social intercourse. a good-natured man recommends himself to all by the spirit which governs him. a good-humored man recommends himself particularly as a companion. a good-tempered man is rarely betrayed into anything which can disturb the serenity of the social circle.
definitions: Naturally mild in temper; not easily provoked.
Having the tail set low and buttocks that fall away sharply from the croup; -- said of certain horses.
Thick-skulled; stupid.
Proceeding from a male and female of different breeds or races; having only one parent of good stock; as, a half-blooded sheep.
Degenerate; mean.
Half-filled. [Obs.] Lions' half-clammed entrails roar food. Marston.
Half-demented; half-witted. [Colloq.]
Imperfectly hatched; as, half-hatched eggs. Gay.
Wanting in heart or spirit; ungenerous; unkind. B. Jonson.
Lacking zeal or courage; lukewarm. H. James.
Imperfectly learned.
Seeing imperfectly; having weak discernment. Bacon.
Hard-featured; ill-looking; as, Vulcan was hard-favored. Dryden.
Unsympathetic; inexorable; cruel; pitiless.  -- Hard"-heart`ed*ness, n.
Wrought with severe labor; elaborate; studied. Swift.
Not sensible to the bit; not easily governed; as, a hard- mouthed horse.
Of a harsh or stern countenance; hard-featured. Burke.
Timorous; timid; easily frightened. Ainsworth.
Wild; giddy; flighty; rash; thoughtless. [Colloq.] They had a quarrel with Sir Thomas Newcome's own son, a harum-scarum lad. Thackeray.
Preying on the heart.
Dull; stupid. "Gross heavy-headed fellows." Beau. & Fl.
Haunted by devils; hellish. Dryden.
Having a strong, deep, or glaring color; flushed. Shak.
Vivid; strong or forcible in representation; hence, exaggerated; as, high-colored description.
Having lofty arches. "The high-embowed roof." Milton.
Elated. Young.
Full of courage or nobleness; high-souled.  -- High"-heart`ed*ness, n.
Having abundance of mettle; ardent; full of fire; as, a high- mettled steed.
Looking upward; supercilious. Shak.
Wrought with fine art or skill; elaborate. [Obs.] Pope.
Worked up, or swollen, to a high degree; as, a highwrought passion. "A high-wrought flood." Shak.
Staying at home; not gadding. Home-keeping youth have ever homely wits. Shak.
Having the hands horny and callous from labor.
Having a fierly spirit; hot-headed.
Impolite; rude.
Ill-bred. Shak.
Of bad temper; morose; crabbed; sour; peevish; fretful; quarrelsome.
Unhealthy; ill-conditioned. [Obs.] So ill-tempered I am grown, that I am afraid I shall catch cold, while all the world is afraid to melt away. Pepys.
Inciting to motion; -- applied to that action which, in the case of muscular motion, commences in the nerve centers, and excites the muscles to contraction. Opposed to excito-motor.
Of or pertaining to Indo-China (i. e., Farther India, or India beyond the Ganges).
Of or relating to the English who are born or reside in India; Anglo-Indian.
Hard-hearted; unfeeling; cruel; as, an iron-hearted master. Cowper.
Double-headed.
Having kindness of nature; sympathetic; characterized by a humane disposition; as, a kind-hearted landlord. To thy self at least kind-hearted prove. Shak.
Saving labor; adapted to supersede or diminish the labor of men; as, laborsaving machinery.
Having large hands, Fig.: Taking, or giving, in large quantities; rapacious or bountiful.
Having the sandy brown color of the European larks.
Not having a full complement of men; as, a vessel light-handed.
Disordered in the head; dilirious. Walpole.
Thoughtless; heedless; volatile; unsteady; fickle; loose. "Light- headed, weak men." Clarendon.  -- Light"-head`ed*ness, n.
Lively in walking or running; brisk; light-footed.
Nimble; swift of foot. Sir P. Sidney.
Unsettled; unsteady; volatile; not considerate.  -- Light"-mind`ed*ness, n.
Having light and active wings; volatile; fleeting. Shak.
White-livered; cowardly.
Beset with snares; insnared, as with birdlime. L. Addison.
Very brave; brave and magnanimous. Sir W. Scott.
Able to see objects at a great distance; hence, having great foresight; sagacious; farseeing.
Able to see objects distinctly at a distance, but not close at hand; hypermetropic.
Having a long tongue.
Talkative; babbling; loquacious. Shak.
Having a long waist; long from the armpits to the armpits to the bottom of the waist; -- said of persons.
Long from the part about the neck or shoulder, or from the armpits, to the bottom of the weist, or to the skirt; -- said of garments; as, a long-waisted coat.
Having a loud voice; talking or sounding noisily; noisily impudent.

Having, employing, or exerting, a low degree of pressure. Low- pressure steam engine, a steam engine in which low steam is used; often applied to a condensing engine even when steam at high pressure is used. See Steam engine.
Deficient in animation and courage; dejected; depressed; not sprightly.  -- Low"-spir`it*ed*ness, n.
Feigned; insincere. "Make-believe reverence." G. Eliot.
Having the edge veined or spotted with different colors like marble, as a book.
See Mealy-mouthed.
Of or pertaining to law as affected by medical facts.
Having a medium size; as, a medium-sized man.
White-livered; cowardly; timorous.
Affording profitable returns; lucrative; as, a money-making business.
Sussessful in gaining money, and devoted to that aim; as, a money- making man.
Naked as when born.
Driven or actuated by a motor, esp. by an individual electric motor. An electric motor forms an integral part of many machine tools in numerous modern machine shops.
Having the basal joints of the legs converted into jaws.
Dull; stupid.
Of or pertaining to Neo-Hegelianism.
Affected by a tremor, or by a nervous disease; weakened; overcome by some violent influence or sensation; shoked.
Going or traveling in the night. Gay.
Having a noble mind; honorable; magnanimous.  -- No"ble-mind`ed*ness, n.
Full of nooks, angles, or corners. [Obs. or Prov. Eng.] That nook-shotten isle of Albion. Shak.
Between oblong and ovate, but inclined to the latter.
Like an old woman; anile.  -- Old`-wom"an*ish*ness, n.
Candid; frank; generous. Dryden.  -- O"pen-heart`ed*ly, adv.  -- O"pen-heart`ed*ness, n. Walton.
Having the mouth open; gaping; hence, greedy; clamorous. L'Estrange.
Oblong. with one end narrower than the other; ovato-oblong.
Same as Ovate-oblong.
Of or pertaining to both North and South America.
Belonging to, or representing, the whole Church of England; used less strictly, to include the Protestant Episcopal Church of the United States; as, the Pan-Anglican Conference at Lambeth, in 1888.
Having a motley coat, or coat of divers colors. Shak.
Having a very narrow stern; -- said of a vessel.
Speaking with plain, unreserved sincerity; also, spoken sincerely; as, plain-spoken words. Dryden.
Plane or flat on one side, and convex on the other; as, a plano-convex lens. See Convex, and Lens.
Eating, or subsisting on, plants; as, a plant-eating beetle.
Having flat, or leaflike, gills, as the bivalve mollusks.
See Pockmarked.
Uncommonly nice and exact; precise; particular. You are rather point-devise in your accouterments. Shak. Thus he grew up, in logic point-devise, Perfect in grammar, and in rhetoric nice. Longfellow.
Capable of being seized.
Of or pertaining to movement produced by action of the mind or will.
Having a face left as it comes from the quarry and not smoothed with the chisel or point; -- said of stones.
Having ready wit Shak.
Capable of luminescence under the action of cathode rays, X rays, or any of the allied forms of radiation. -- Ra`di*o- ac*tiv"i*ty, n.
Rattle-headed. "A noisy, rattle-pated fellow." W. Irving.
Having a sharp, lean, or thin back; as, a razor-backed hog, perch, etc.
Having ready wit.
Both renal and portal. See Portal.
Containing a right angle or right angles; as, a right-angled triangle.
Using the right hand habitually, or more easily than the left.
Having the same direction or course as the movement of the hands of a watch seen in front; -- said of the motion of a revolving object looked at from a given direction.

Having the whorls rising from left to right; dextral; -- said of spiral shells. See Illust. of Scalaria. Right-handed screw, a screw, the threads of which, like those of a common wood screw, wind spirally in such a direction that screw advances away from the observer when turned with a right-handed movement in a fixed nut.
Having a right or honest mind.  -- Right"-mind`ed*ness, n.
Having a back like that of roach; -- said of a horse whose back a convex instead of a concave curve.
Having the color of a pink rose; rose-pink; of a delicate pink color.
Uncommonly beautiful; hence, extravagantly fine or pleasing; alluring; as, rose-colored anticipations.
Feather-footed; as, a rough-footed dove. [R.] Sherwood.
Having the legs covered with feathers; -- said of a bird. rough-legged hawk. (Zoöl.) See Roughleg.
Having a round back or shoulders; round-shouldered.
Having the wings covered with small scalelike structures, as the lepidoptera; scaly-winged.
Scale-winged.
Having a scraggy neck.
Of the rank or degree below the best highest; inferior; second- rate; as, a second-class house; a second-class passage.
Lowering or humbling one's self.
Accused by one's self or by one's conscience. "Die self- accused." Cowper.
Assumed by one's own act, or without authority.
Assured by or of one's self; self-reliant; complacent.
Being of a single color; -- applied to flowers, animals, and textile fabrics.
Created by one's self; not formed or constituted by another.
Refusing to gratify one's self; self-sacrificing.  -- Self`-de*ny"ing*ly, adv.
Devised by one's self.
Devoted in person, or by one's own will. Hawthorne.
Evident without proof or reasoning; producing certainty or conviction upon a bare presentation to the mind; as, a self-evident proposition or truth.  -- Self`-ev"i*dent*ly, adv.
Having the power or property of healing itself.
Voluntarily taken on one's self; as, self-imposed tasks.
Kindled of itself, or without extraneous aid or power. Dryden.
Knowing one's self, or one's own character, powers, and limitations.
Knowing of itself, without help from another.
Disposed or arranged by an action originating in one's self or in itself. These molecular blocks of salt are self-posited. Tyndall.
Reliant upon one's self; trusting to one's own powers or judgment.
Seeking one's own interest or happiness; selfish. Arbuthnot.
Having eyes which are not elevated on a stalk; -- opposed to stalk-eyed. Sessile-eyed Crustacea, the Arthrostraca.
Stitched according to a formal pattern. "An old set-stiched chair, valanced, and fringed with party-colored worsted bobs." Sterne.
Having an acute or nicely discerning mind.
Silly; simple-minded; stupid. Taylor (1630)
Having a thick and bushy head of hair.
Short of, or lacking the regular number of, servants or helpers.
Speaking in a quick or short manner; hence, gruff; curt. [Colloq.]
Affected with shortness of breath; having a quick, difficult respiration, as dyspnoic and asthmatic persons. May.
Having a broad, flat nose; as, the shovel-nosed duck, or shoveler.
Disordered in the brain.
Engaged in, or given to, seeing sights; eager for novelties or curiosities.
