Having the sinews under the belly shrunk by excessive fatigue.
Constituting or being one of sixty-four equal parts into which a thing is divided. Sixty-fourth note (Mus.), the sixty-fourth part of a whole note; a hemi-demi-semiquaver.
Having a disposition or temper habitually sober.  -- So"ber-mind`ed*ness, n.
Having softness or tenderness of heart; susceptible of pity or other kindly affection; gentle; meek.  -- Soft"-heart`ed*ness, n.
Having fine supported by spinous fin rays; -- said of certain fishes.
Having the tail quills ending in sharp, naked tips. Spine- tailed swift. (Zoöl.) See Spinetail (a).
Having the bill expanded and spatulate at the end.
Characterized by a pretentious, boastful, exaggerated style; defiantly or extravagantly bombastic; as, a spread-eagle orator; a spread-eagle speech. [Colloq.& Humorous]
Fascinated by the stage; seized by a passionate desire to become an actor.
Not favored by the stars; ill-fated. [Poetic] Shak. Such in my star-crossed destiny. Massinger.
Wound by mechanism connected with the stem; as, a stem-winding watch.
Obstinate. J. H. Newman.
Stubborn; inflexibly obstinate; contumacious; as, stiff-necked pride; a stiff-necked people. Ex. xxxii. 9.
Having the quill feathers of the tail somewhat rigid.
Having a bill like that of the stork.
Acting without concealment, obliquity, or compromise; hence, unqualified; thoroughgoing. [Colloq. U.S.] Straight-out and generous indignation. Mrs. Stowe.
Bound with stays. Let nature have scope to fashion the body as she thinks best; we have few well-shaped that are strait-laced. Locke.
Restricted; stiff; constrained. [R.] Fuller.
Rigid in opinion; strict in manners or morals.
Shaped like a strap; ligulate; as, a strap-shaped corolla.

Having a short, thick tail. Stump-tailed lizard (Zoöl.), a singular Australian scincoid lizard (Trachydosaurus rugosus) having a short, thick tail resembling its head in form; -- called also sleeping lizard.
Having a prominent, overhanging belly. Shak.
Shaped like a sword; ensiform, as the long, flat leaves of the Iris, cattail, and the like.
Having a sickly complexion; pale. Burton.
Shedding tears; tender. [Poetic] "Tear-falling pity." Shak.
Having a thick skull; stupid.
Affected with thick wind.
Having a thin skin; hence, sensitive; irritable.
Having a head armed with thorns or spines. Thorn-headed worm (Zoöl.), any worm of the order Acanthocephala; -- called also thornhead.
Said of games or contests where three persons play against each other, or two against one; as, a three-handed game of cards.
Producing three leaves; as, three-leaved nightshade.
Consisting of three distinct leaflets; having the leaflets arranged in threes. Three-leaved nightshade. See Trillium.
Having three nerves. Three-nerved leaf (Bot.), a leaf having three distinct and prominent ribs, or nerves, extending from the base.
Divided into, or consisting of, three parts; tripartite. Three- parted leaf (Bot.), a leaf divided into three parts down to the base, but not entirely separate.
Having a cross section in the form of an equilateral triangle; -- said especially of a kind of file.
Consisting of, or having, three valves; opening with three valves; as, a three-valved pericarp.
Hastening to devour; furious.
Honored for a long time; venerable, and worthy of honor, by reason of antiquity, or long continuance.
Of a faithful heart; honest; sincere; not faithless or deceitful; as, a truhearted friend.  -- True"-heart`ed*ness, n.
Having two distinct capsules; bicapsular.
Not called for; not required or needed; improper; gratuitous; wanton.
Not looked for; unexpected; as, an unlooked-for event.
Not subjected to Roman arms or customs. J. Whitaker.
Not subjected to the principles or usages of the Roman Catholic Church.
Having a top, or head, shaped like the top of a covered wagon, or resembling in section or outline an inverted U, thus as, a wagonheaded ceiling.
Having a roof, or top, shaped like an inverted U; wagon-headed.

Having warm blood; -- applied especially to those animals, as birds and mammals, which have warm blood, or, more properly, the power of maintaining a nearly uniform temperature whatever the temperature of the surrounding air. See Homoiothermal.
Having strong affection; cordial; sincere; hearty; sympathetic.  -- Warm"-heart`ed*ness, n.

Filled or saturated with water so as to be heavy, unmanageable, or loglike; -- said of a vessel, when, by receiving a great quantity of water into her hold, she has become so heavy as not to be manageable by the helm.
Having little courage; of feeble spirit; dispirited; faint- hearted. "Weak-hearted enemies." Shak.
Having a thin, sharp face, like a weasel.
Having the fingers united by a web for a considerable part of their length.
Having the form of a wedge; cuneiform. Wedge-formed characters. See Arrow-headed characters, under Arrowheaded.
Having the shape of a wedge; cuneiform.
Broad and truncate at the summit, and tapering down to the base; as, a wedge-shaped leaf.

Having a tail which has the middle pair of feathers longest, the rest successively and decidedly shorter, and all more or less attenuate; -- said of certain birds. See Illust. of Wood hoopoe, under Wood. Wedge-tailed eagle, an Australian eagle (Aquila audax) which feeds on various small species of kangaroos, and on lambs; -- called also mountain eagle, bold eagle, and eagle hawk.  -- Wedge-tailed gull, an arctic gull (Rhodostethia rosea) in which the plumage is tinged with rose; -- called also Ross's gull.
Ripe for weeping; ready to weep. [Obs.] Shak.
Handsome; wellformed; beautiful; pleasing to the eye. Rachel was beautiful and well-favored. Gen. xxix. 17.
Having a good intention.
Good-natured; kind. Well-natured, temperate, and wise. Denham.
Shaped like a wheel.
Expanding into a flat, circular border at top, with scarcely any tube; as, a wheel-shaped corolla.
Having an undivided hoof, as the horse.
Representing the whole figure; -- said of a picture or statue.  -- n.
A portrait or statue representing the whole figure.
Thoroughly imbued with a right spirit; noble-minded; devoted.
Having too rank or forward a growth for winter. When either corn is winter-proud, or other plants put forth and bud too early. Holland.
Wise; knowing; skillful; sapient; erudite; prudent. Ex. xxviii. 3.
Injured or hurt in the withers, as a horse.
Outdoor; exterior. [Obs.] "Her without-door form." Shak.
A term used of beer when the froth of the yeast has reëntered the body of the beer.
Absent in mind; abstracted; preoccupied.  -- Ab`sent-mind"ed*ness, n.  -- Ab`sent-mind"ed*ly, adv.
Dull-witted; stupid. "The addle-brained Oberstein." Motley. Dull and addle-pated. Dryden.
Most beloved. [Obs.] Shak.
Controlled by an evil spirit or by evil passions; wild. [Colloq.]
Of another sort. [Obs.] "Another-gates adventure." Hudibras.
Of another sort. [Archaic] It used to go in another-guess manner. Arbuthnot.
Opposed to the Americans, their aims, or interests, or to the genius of American institutions. Marshall.
Opposed to what is Gallic or French.
Having legs of unequal length, as the badger was thought to have. Shak.
Having prominent, overhanging brows; hence, lowering or sullen.
Dull; stupid. Shak.
Pinched with hunger; starved. "The belly-pinched wolf." Shak.
Dark-visaged; swart.
Having a wicked, malignant disposition; morally bad.
Using foul or scurrilous language; slanderous.
Bloodshot. [Obs.]
Having a cruel, ferocious disposition; bloodthirsty. Dryden.
Impudent; bold.
Shamelessly impudent. Sir T. Browne.
Having a broad brim. A broad-brimmed flat silver plate. Tatler.
Having a broken back; as, a broken-backed chair.
Hogged; so weakened in the frame as to droop at each end; -- said of a ship. Totten.
Having short breath or disordered respiration, as a horse.
Having a large head, like a buffalo; dull; stupid; blundering. [Obs.] So fell this buffle-headed giant. Gayton.
Worldly-minded.
Shining brightly. Shak.
Seeing with clearness; discerning; as, clear-sighted reason
Having the side planks (af a boat) so arranged that the lower edge of each overlaps the upper edge of the plank next below it like clapboards on a house. See Lapstreak.
Closemouthed; silent. "Close-tongued treason." Shak.
Having the foot or hoof divided into two parts, as the ox.
Convex on one side, and flat on the other; plano-convex.
Having the nerves spring from the midrib.
Having an impaired intellect; whimsical; crazy. Pope.
Of the color of cream; light yellow. "Cream-colored horses." Hazlitt.

Acting directly, as one part upon another, without the intervention of other working parts. Direct-acting steam engine, one in which motion is transmitted to the crank without the intervention of a beam or lever; -- also called direct-action steam engine.  -- Direct-acting steam pump, one in which the steam piston rod is directly connected with the pump rod; -- also called direct-action steam pump.
Acting or operating in two directions or with both motions; producing a twofold result; as, a double-acting engine or pump.
Applied to a kind of rowing in which the rowers sit side by side in twos, a pair of oars being worked from each bank or thwart.
Having two hands.
Deceitful; deceptive. Glanvill.
Having two heads; bicipital. Double-headed rail (Railroad), a rail whose flanges are duplicates, so that when one is worn the other may be turned uppermost.
Twice milled or fulled, to render more compact or fine; -- said of cloth; as, double-milled kerseymere.
Like dough; soft. He demeans himself . . . like a dough-kneaded thing. Milton.
Thick-headed; stupid.
Farsighted and strong-sighted; sharp-sighted. Shak.
Deafening; disagreeably loud or shrill; as, ear-splitting strains.
Possessing electrical polarity; positively electrified at one end, or on one surface, and negatively at the other; -- said of a conductor.
Derived from, or dependent upon, vital processes; -- said of certain electric currents supposed by some physiologists to circulate in the nerves of animals.
Having a position intermediate between erect and patent, or spreading.
Standing partially spread and erect; -- said of the wings of certain insects.

Exciting motion; -- said of that portion of the nervous system concerned in reflex action, by which impressions are transmitted to a nerve center and then reflected back so as to produce muscular contraction without sensation or volition.
Outside of the uterus, or womb. Extra-uterine pregnancy (Med.), a condition of pregnancy in which the fetus is not in the uterus, but in the Fallopian tube or in the abdominal cavity.
Hollow or unsound at the core; treacherous; deceitful; perfidious. Bacon.  -- False"*heart`ed*ness, n. Bp. Stillingfleet.
Stretched beyond ordinary limits.
Stretched beyond ordinary limits.
Having a feather-edge; also, having one edge thinner than the other, as a board; -- in the United States, said only of stuff one edge of which is made as thin as practicable.
Feather-headed; frivolous. [Colloq.] Sir W. Scott.
Weak in intellectual power; wanting firmness or constancy; irresolute; vacilating; imbecile. "comfort the feeble-minded." 1 Thess. v. 14.  -- Fee"ble-mind"ed*ness, n.
Inversely ovate, with a deep hollow on each side. Gray.
Of the color of flame; of a bright orange yellow color. Shak.
Having an even lower surface or bottom; as, a flat-bottomed boat.
Hard-hearted. Shak.
Formed by the joint action of a river and the sea, as deposits at the mouths of rivers.
Having four corners or angles.
Swimming in the open sea; -- said of certain marine animals.
Built like a frigate with a raised quarter-deck and forecastle.
Full and large at the bottom, as wigs worn by certain civil officers in Great Britain.
Of great capacity below the water line.
Having a good temper; not easily vexed. See Good-natured.
Having a great belly, bigbellied; pregnant; teeming. Shak.
High-spirited; fearless. [Obs.] Clarendon.
Generous; magnanimous; noble.
Half-bred; imperfect. [R.] "A half-strained villain." Dryden.
Constructed of a timber frame, having the spaces filled in with masonry; -- said of buildings.
Depriving of thought; ecstatic. "Heart-robbing gladness." Spenser.
Stealing the heart or affections; winning.
Wounded to the heart with love or grief. Pope.
Shaped like a helmet; galeate. See Illust. of Galeate.
Finished with great care; polished.
Having or involving a pressure greatly exceeding that of the atmosphere; -- said of steam, air, water, etc., and of steam, air, or hydraulic engines, water wheels, etc.

Fig.: Urgent; intense; as, a high-pressure business or social life. High-pressure engine, an engine in which steam at high pressure is used. It may be either a condensing or a noncondensing engine. Formerly the term was used only of the latter. See Steam engine.
Reaching high or upward; hence, ambitious; aspiring. Shak.
Enriched with spice and condiments; hence, exciting; piquant.
Pompous; noisy; ostentatious; as, high-sounding words or titles.
Full of spirit or natural fire; haughty; courageous; impetuous; not brooking restraint or opposition.
Inflated; boastful.
Hoity-toity.
Having permanent horns with a bony core, as cattle.
Keeping at home.
Soft to sweet in speech; persuasive. Shak.
Sweet speaking; persuasive; seductive. Shak.
Horror-stricken; horrified. M. Arnold.
Round-shoulded.
Secret; clandestine; sly.
Confused; disorderly; slovenly; mean; as, hugger-mugger doings.
Dipped in the gall of the fabulous hydra; poisonous; deadly. Cowper.
Incitomotor.

Aryan; -- applied to the languages of India and Europe which are derived from the prehistoric Aryan language; also, pertaining to the people or nations who speak these languages; as, the Indo- European or Aryan family. The common origin of the Indo-European nations. Tylor.
Same as Aryan, and Indo-European.
Pertaining to or denoting the Teutonic family of languages as related to the Sanskrit, or derived from the ancient Aryan language.
Worn out with journeying. [Obs.] Shak.
Red; -- from a tradition that Judas Iscariot had red hair and beard. There's treachery in that Judas-colored beard. Dryden.
Fantastic; restless; as, kicksy-wicksy flames. Nares.
Obsequious; fawning; cringing. "Knee-crooking knave." Shak.
Having lantern jaws or long, thin jaws; as, a lantern-jawed person.
Having a large or generous heart or disposition; noble; liberal.  -- Large"-heart`ed*ness, n.
Having the general shape or outline of a leg of mutton; as, a leg-of-mutton, or shoulder-of-mutton, sail.
Pertaining to the literature of law.
Free from grief or anxiety; gay; cheerful; merry.  -- Light"-heart`ed*ly, adv.  -- Light"-heart"ed*ness, n.
Of a linear shape.
Having a color like liver; dark reddish brown.
Having the power of retaining the breath for a long time; long- winded.
Having one's thoughts directed toward mean or insignificant subjects.
Having the spirit of a male; vigorous; courageous. [R.] B. Jonson.

Using soft words; plausible; affectedly or timidly delicate of speech; unwilling to tell the truth in plain language. "Mealy-mouthed philanthropies." Tennyson. She was a fool to be mealy-mouthed where nature speaks so plain. L'Estrange. -- Meal"y-mouth`ness, n.
Of a mean spirit; base; groveling.  -- Mean"-spir`it*ed*ness, n.
Having a medium compass between the soprano and contralto; -- said of the voice of a female singer.  -- n.
A mezzo-soprano voice.
A person having such a voice.
Having a mind of a jester; foolish. Shak.
Dull-spirited. Shak.
Of narrow mental scope; illiberal; mean.  -- Nar"row-mind`ed*ness, n.
Between the neural arch and the centrum of a vertebra; as, the neurocentral suture. Huxley.
Not Episcopal; not pertaining to the Episcopal church or system.
Having an obtuse angle; as, an obtuse-angled triangle.

Formed according to old or obsolete fashion or pattern; adhering to old customs or ideas; as, an old-fashioned dress, girl. "Old-fashioned men of wit." Addison. This old-fashioned, quaint abode. Longfellow.
Colored with different tints; variegated; as, a party-colored flower. "Parti-colored lambs." Shak.
Of the color of a peach blossom. "Peach-colored satin." Shak.
Practicing plain dealing; artless. See Plain dealing, under Dealing. Shak.
Frank; sincere; artless. Milton.  -- Plain"-heart`ed*ness, n.
Plane or flat on one side, and concave on the other; as, a plano-concave lens. See Lens.
Plane or flat on one side, and conical on the other. Grew.
Having a broad, flat face.
Of a mean spirit; cowardly; base.  -- Poor"-spir`it*ed*ness, n.
Situated back of the temporal bone or the temporal region of the skull; -- applied especially to a bone which usually connects the supraclavicle with the skull in the pectoral arch of fishes.  -- n.
A post-temporal bone.
Situated behind the tympanum, or in the skull, behind the auditory meatus.
Having a pouch mouth; blobber-lipped.
Affected with dry rot; reduced to dust by rot. See Dry rot, under Dry. [U.S.]
Spoken or speaking prettily. [Colloq.]
Controlled or oppressed by priests; as, a priest-ridden people. Swift.
Having a blunt or button-shaped extremity; -- said of cutting instruments.
Public-spirited.  -- Pub"lic-mind`ed*ness, n.
Having the head full of confused notions. Johnson.
Acute of smell.
Having quick sight or acute discernment; quick to see or to discern. Locke. --Quick"-sight`ed*ness, n.
Having long and spatulate, or racket-shaped, tail feathers.
Noisy; giddy; unsteady.
Of or pertaining to both the rectum and the uterus.
Of or pertaining to both the rectum and the bladder.
Having a right heart or disposition.  -- Right"-heart`ed*ness, n.
Straight; direct.
Having circular streaks or lines on the body; as, ring-streaked goats.
HAving ripple marks.
Having a rough grain or fiber; hence, figuratively, having coarse traits of character; not polished; brisque.
Having the outline of the upper part concave like the seat of a saddle.
Having a low back and high neck, as a horse.
Shaped like a saddle. Specifically:
Tubular, with a speading border. See Hypocraterimorphous.
pertaining to, or involving, sans-culottism; radical; revolutionary; Jacobinical. Carlyle.
Adapted for forming a screw by cutting; as, a screw-cutting lathe.
Bordering on the sea; situated beside the sea. Drayton.
Applying to or by one's self.
Exiled voluntarily.
Begotten by one's self, or one's own powers.
Centered in itself, or in one's self. There hangs the ball of earth and water mixt, Self-centered and unmoved. Dryden.
Deceived or misled respecting one's self by one's own mistake or error.
Corrupted or depraved by one's self. Milton.
Educated by one's own efforts, without instruction, or without pecuniary assistance from others.
Having the right of electing one's self, or, as a body, of electing its own members.
Existing of or by himself,independent of any other being or cause; -- as, God is the only self-existent being.
Springing from vainglory or vanity; vain; boastful. Dryden.
Ignorant of one's self.
Possessing in itself the property of emitting light. Sir D. Brewster.
The act of disposing or arranging one's self or itself. The self-positing of the molecules. R. Watts.
Reproved by one's own conscience or one's own sense of guilt.
Of or pertaining to the Semi-Pelagians, or their tenets.
Shallow-brained.
Having quick or acute sight; -- used literally and figuratively.  -- Sharp`-sight`ed*ness, n.
Having elytra, or wing cases, as a beetle.
Having short intervals between the joints; -- said of a plant or an animal, especially of a horse whose pastern is too short.
Having a short waist.
Having a throat which produces a shrill note. [R.] Shak.

Wearing silk stockings (which among men were formerly worn chiefly by the luxurious or aristocratic); hence, elegantly dressed; aristocratic; luxurious; -- chiefly applied to men, often by way of reproach.
Artless; guileless; simple-hearted; undesigning; unsuspecting; devoid of duplicity. Blackstone.  -- Sim"ple-mind`ed*ness, n.
Having simplicity of action; especially (Mach.), acting or exerting force during strokes in one direction only; -- said of a reciprocating engine, pump, etc.
Having but one hand, or one workman; also, alone; unassisted.
Having a single purpose; hence, artless; guileless; single- hearted.
Heavy with sleep.
Speaking smoothly; plausible; flattering; smooth-tongued.
Heavy; dull. Shak.
Having a forked tongue, as that of snakes and some lizards.
Having the sails extended upon yards suspended horizontally by the middle, as distinguished from fore-and-aft sails; thus, a ship and a brig are square-rigged vessels.
Bred in conformity to a standard. Specif., applied to a registered trotting horse which comes up to the standard adopted by the National Association of Trotting-horse Breeders. [U. S.]
Spangled or studded with stars. Star-spangled banner, the popular name for the national ensign of the United States. F. S. Key.
Embracing the stem with its base; amplexicaul; as a leaf or petiole.
Pertaining to, or illustrating, the hypothetical space relations of atoms in the molecule; as, a stereo-chemic formula.
Obstinate; stubborn; contumacious. Ezek. ii. 4.
Ever closing. [Obs.] "Still-clothing waters." Shak.
Hard-hearted; cruel; pitiless; unfeeling.
Being accustomed to tell stories.  -- n.
The act or practice of telling stories.
Having a brave heart; courageous.  -- Stout"-heart"ed*ness, n.
Parsimonious; sparing; niggardly. [R.] -- Strait"-hand`ed*ness, n. [R.]
Being of a straw color. See Straw color, under Straw, n.
Having a vigorous mind; esp., having or affecting masculine qualities of mind; -- said of women.  -- Strong"-mind`ed*ness, n.
See Surangular.
Above, or on the dorsal side of, the ethmoid bone or cartilage.
Having a sweet scent or smell; fragrant. Sweet-scented shrub (Bot.), a shrub of the genus Calycanthus, the flowers of which, when crushed, have a fragrance resembling that of strawberries.
Having great tenderness; easily moved. [Obs.] Shak.
Having a thick skin; hence, not sensitive; dull; obtuse. Holland.
Having a thick skull; hence, dull; heavy; stupid; slow to learn.
Being one of thirty-two equal parts into which anything is divided. Thirty-second note (Mus.), the thirty-second part of a whole note; a demi-semiquaver.
Having the form of a thread; filiform.
Having three acute or setigerous points; tricuspidate.
Measuring thirty inches by twenty-five; -- said of portraitures. Three-quarter length, a portrait showing the figure to the hips only.
Uncertain; inconstant; slippery. [Obs. & R.] Beau. & Fl.
Shaped like a tongue; specifically (Bot.), linear or oblong, and fleshy, blunt at the end, and convex beneath; as, a tongue-shaped leaf.
Having three heads; three-headed; as, the triple-headed dog Cerberus.
White, with spots of black, bay, or sorrel; as, a trout-colored horse.

Designating, or pert. to, a mixed racial type including the Afghans, and characterized chiefly by stature above mean, fair complexion, dark, or sometimes gray, eyes, brachycephaly, and very long, prominent, and moderately narrow nose.
Slow-footed. [R.] "Turtle-footed Peace." Ford.
Having twenty-four leaves to a sheet; as, a twenty-fourmo form, book, leaf, size, etc.  -- n.
A book composed of sheets, each of which is folded into twenty- four leaves; hence, indicating more or less definitely a size of book whose sheets are so folded; -- usually written 24mo, or 24º.
Partaking of the nature both of vegetable and animal matter; -- a term sometimes applied to vegetable albumen and gluten, from their resemblance to similar animal products.
Pertaining both to the vulva and the uterus.
Balanced or considered with reference to public weal. [Obs.] Shak.
Kept in port or at anchor by storms; delayed by bad weather; as, a weather-bound vessel.
Correctly informed; provided with information; well furnished with authentic knowledge; intelligent.
Polite; well-bred; complaisant; courteous. Dryden.
Being well folded. [Obs.] "Her well-plighted frock." Spenser.
Having a white front; as, the white-fronted lemur. White- fronted goose (Zoöl.), the white brant, or snow goose. See Snow goose, under Snow.
Having a pale look; feeble; hence, cowardly; pusillanimous; dastardly. They must not be milksops, nor white-livered knights. Latimer.
Beaten or harassed by the severe weather of winter. Spenser.
Of or pertaining to a church modeled on the English Reformation; Anglican; -- sometimes restricted to the ritualistic or High Church section of the Church of England.
Angularly toothed, as certain leaves.
Of another kind. [Obs.] Sir P. Sidney.
Having thick lips. "A blobber-lipped shell." Grew.
Having the hair matted with clotted blood. [Obs. & R.] The blood-boltered Banquo smiles upon me. Shak.
Receiving the charge at the breech instead of at the muzzle.
Resembling a bristle in form; as, a bristle-shaped leaf.
Having a ruptured belly. [R.]
Having the spirits depressed or crushed by grief or despair. She left her husband almost broken-hearted. Macaulay.
Having a head like a buckler.
Diagonal. [Colloq.]

Of or pertaining to the central nervous system consisting of the brain and spinal cord. Cerebro-spinal fluid (Physiol.), a serous fluid secreted by the membranes covering the brain and spinal cord.  -- Cerebro-spinal meningitis, Cerebro-spinal fever (Med.), a dangerous epidemic, and endemic, febrile disease, characterized by inflammation of the membranes of the brain and spinal cord, giving rise to severe headaches, tenderness of the back of the neck, paralysis of the ocular muscles, etc. It is sometimes marked by a cutaneous eruption, when it is often called spotted fever. It is not contagious.
Five-spotted. [R.] Shak.
Well-propotioned; symmetrical. [Poetic] Shak.
See Clinker-built.
Having a coarse grain or texture, as wood; hence, wanting in refinement.
Concave on one side and convex on the other, as an eggshell or a crescent.
Specifically, having such a combination of concave and convex sides as makes the focal axis the shortest line between them. See Illust. under Lens.
Convex on botConvex, a.
Shaped like a diamond or rhombus.
Coupled without intermediate connections, as an engine and a dynamo.
Making contrary declarations on the same subject; deceitful. Likewise must the deacons be grave, not double-tongued. 1 Tim. iii. 8.
Untidy; sluttish; slatternly. W. Irving.
Having a mind devoted to earthly things; worldly-minded; -- opposed to spiritual-minded.  -- Earth"ly-mind`ed*ness, n.
Pertaining to electrometry; made by means of electrometer; as, an electrometrical experiment.

Producing electro-motion; producing, or tending to produce, electricity or an electric current; causing electrical action or effects. Electro-motive force (Physics), the force which produces, or tends to produce, electricity, or an electric current; sometimes used to express the degree of electrification as equivalent to potential, or more properly difference of potential.
Not prescribed by official duty.
Giddy; frivolous; foolish. [Colloq.] G. Eliot.
Light-heeled; gay; frisky; frolicsome. [Colloq.]
Having the veins (of a leaf) diverging from the two sides of a midrib.
Producing twins. [R.] Bailey.
Having a kind or gentle disposition. Shak.  -- Gen"tle-heart`ed*ness, n.
Hastate.
Having the surface roughly shaped or faced with the stonecutter's hammer; -- said of building stone.
Having a lofty spirit; haughty. [Obs.] Shak.
Insincere; deceitful; not sound and true; having a cavity or decayed spot within.
Struck with horror; horrified. Blank and horror-stricken faces. C. Kingsley.

Pertaining to, employed in, or produced by, the evolution of electricity by means of a battery in which water or steam is used. Hydro-electric machine (Physics), an apparatus invented by Sir William Armstrong of England for generating electricity by the escape of high-pressure steam from a series of jets connected with a strong boiler, in which the steam is produced.
Situated below the axil, as a bud.
Dexterous in taking and conveying away; thievish; pilfering; addicted to petty thefts. Fuller.
Made of linen and wool; hence, of different and unsuitable parts; mean. Johnson.
Adhering to facts; not turning aside from absolute realities; not fanciful or imaginative; commonplace; dry.
Of or pertaining to micro-chemistry; as, a micro-chemical test.
Having a face of a mulberry color, or blotched as if with mulberry stains.
Receiving its charge through the muzzle; as, a muzzle-loading rifle.
Pointed as needles.

Designating, or pertaining to, a group of modern economists who hold to the Malthusianism doctrine that permanent betterment of the general standard of living is impossible without decrease of competition by limitation of the number of births. -- Ne`o- Mal*thu"sian, Ne`o-Mal*thu"sian*ism, n.
Of or pert. to Neo-Scholasticism.
Blooming in the night. Night-blooming cereus. (Bot.) See Note under Cereus.
Having oblique angles; as, an oblique-angled triangle.
See under Out, adv.
Having an ovate form, but with a subulate tip or extremity.
Struck with a panic, or sudden fear. Burke.
Acting by the operation of both light and electricity; -- said of apparatus for producing pictures by electric light.
Pert. to, or capable of developing, photo-electricity.
Timid; easily frightened; chicken-hearted. Beau. & Fl.
Pigeon-hearted.
Having opposite surfaces exactly plane and parallel, as a piece of glass.
Smooth and awl-shaped. See Subulate.
Public-spirited. [R.]
Stupid. [Colloq.]
Having the principal veins radiating, or diverging, from the apex of the petiole; -- said of such leaves as those of the grapevine, most maples, and the castor-oil plant.
Giddy; rattle-headed.
Between rhomboid and ovate, or oval, in shape.
Having the power of second-sight. Addison.
Causing secretion; -- said of nerves which go to glands and influence secretion.

Capable of assuming a desired position or condition with relation to other parts, under varying circumstances, without requiring to be adjusted by hand; -- said of a piece in machinery. Self-adjusting bearing (Shafting), a bearing which is supported in such a manner that it may tip to accomodate flexure or displacement of the shaft.
Approving one's own action or character by one's own judgment. One self-approving hour whole years outweighs Of stupid starers and of loud huzzas. Pope.
asserting one's self, or one's own rights or claims; hence, putting one's self forward in a confident or assuming manner.
Disposed to self-assertion; self-asserting.
Centering in one's self.
Having an overweening opinion of one's own powers, attainments; vain; conceited.  -- Self`-con*ceit"ed*ness, n.
Confident of one's own strength or powers; relying on one's judgment or ability; self-reliant.  -- Self`-con"fi*dent*ly, adv.
Having the two things that are conjugate parts of the same figure; as, self-conjugate triangles.
Conscious of one's acts or state as belonging to, or originating in, one's self. "My self-conscious worth." Dryden.
Conscious of one's self as an object of the observation of others; as, the speaker was too self-conscious.
Consuming one's self or itself.
Having self-control; reserved; uncommunicative; wholly engrossed in one's self.

Having all the essential working parts connected by a bedplate or framework, or contained in a case, etc., so that mutual relations of the parts do not depend upon fastening outside of the machine itself. Self-contained steam engine. (a) A steam engine having both bearings for the crank shaft attached to the frame of the engine. (b) A steam engine and boiler combined and fastened together; a portable steam engine.
Convicted by one's own consciousness, knowledge, avowal, or acts.
Defending, or tending to defend, one's own person, property, or reputation.
Dependent on one's self; self-depending; self-reliant.
Depending on one's self.
Devouring one's self or itself. Danham.
Having power to diffuse itself; diffusing itself. Norris.

Designating, or pert. to, any of various steels that harden when heated to above a red heat and cooled in air, usually in a blast of cold air with moderate rapidity, without quenching. Such steels are alloys of iron and carbon with manganese, tungsten and manganese, chromium, molybdenum and manganese, etc. They are chiefly used as high-speed steels. -- Self`-hard"en*ed, a.
Imparting by one's own, or by its own, powers and will. Norris.
Having or manifesting an exaggerated idea of one's own importance or merit.
Indulging one's appetites, desires, etc., freely.
Having a high opinion of one's self; opinionated; conceited. South.
Perplexed by doubts originating in one's own mind.
Composed or tranquill in mind, manner, etc.; undisturbed.
Regulated by one's self or by itself.
Made up of parts, as molecules or atoms, which mutually repel each other; as, gases are self-repelling.
Reproving one's self; reproving by consciousness of guilt.

Designating, or pertaining to, any engine (called an Internal- combustion engine) in which the heat or pressure energy necessary to produce motion is developed in the engine cylinder, as by the explosion of a gas, and not in a separate chamber, as in a steam- engine boiler. The gas used may be a fixed gas, or one derived from alcohol, ether, gasoline (petrol), naphtha, oil (petroleum), etc. There are three main classes: (1) gas engines proper, using fixed gases, as coal, blast-furnace, or producer gas; (2) engines using the vapor of a volatile fluid, as the typical gasoline (petrol) engine;

oil engines, using either an atomized spray or the vapor (produced by heat) of a comparatively heavy oil, as petroleum or kerosene. In all of these the gas is mixed with a definite amount of air, the charge is composed in the cylinder and is then exploded either by a flame of gas (flame ignition -- now little used), by a hot tube (tube ignition) or the like, by an electric spark (electric ignition, the usual method is gasoline engines, or by the heat of compression, as in the Diesel engine. Gas and oil engines are chiefly of the stationary type. Gasoline engines are largely used for automobile vehicles, boats, etc. Most internal-combustion engines use the Otto (four-stroke) cycle, though many use the two-stroke cycle. They are almost universally trunk engines and single-acting. Because of the intense heat produced by the frequent explosions, the cylinders must be cooled by a water jacket (water-cooled) or by air currents (air cooled) to give the maximum thermodynamic efficiency and to avoid excessive friction or seizing.
